<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Cut Defense Equipment Spending Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Defense Agency plans to
slash spending on major defense equipment by about 5 percent in
fiscal 1998 to maintain zero growth in overall defense spending,
Kyodo News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The cut will translate into a reduction of some 40 billion yen
(339 million U.S. dollars) from the 841 billion yen (7.1 billion
dollars) budgeted on equipment spending in fiscal 1997, the
report quoted Defense Agency sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a decision by the Japanese government in
June to rein in growth in defense expenditure and to cut spending
on key equipment by 920 billion yen (7.8 billion dollars) over the
fiscal 1998-2000 period as part of efforts to balance the state
budget.
</P>
<P>
Besides major equipment, the agency will also cut spending on
logistics facilities, training and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
To further curtail costs, the agency will shift purchases from
special defense-designed sources to the general market.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the agency decided to slash the so-called sympathy
outlays given to United States troops in Japan over the next three
years. The cut will be the first since Japan began to partially cover
such costs in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
