<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia today insisted that they would not enter into negotiations
with rival factions unless the militia's prisoners of war are
released.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's deputy foreign minister, Abdul Jaleel, said the
Taliban want some confidence-building measures in the form of
release of prisoners before they could begin meaningful peace
talks with the rival northern alliance, according to reports
monitored here today.
</P>
<P>
"The northern alliance leaders should create an atmosphere of
mutual trust to make talks meaningful and substantive," Jaleel
said after a meeting with U.N. Special Envoy Norber Holl in
Kandahar, about 450 km southwest of the capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance, based in Mazar-e-Sharif and led
mainly by Afghanistan's former military chief Ahmad Masood and
Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik, has refused the Taliban's such demand.
</P>
<P>
The northern alliance would not release any Taliban's prisoners
before a negotiated settlement of the Afghan conflict, Malik said
on Tuesday after talks with Holl in Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km
northwest of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Taliban alliance has demanded the demilitarization of
Kabul before they could agree to a ceasefire, while the Taliban
have laid the release of their prisoners as a pre-condition for
entering into peace talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
