<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Turkmenistan Push for Talks on Caspian Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Turkmenistan's President Saparmurat Niyazov today called on
the Caspian countries to speed up negotiations over the disputed
oil fields in the Caspian Sea, Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting here today, the two presidents said that the five
littoral states - Russia, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan and
Iran - should accelerate negotiations on the legal status of
the oil-rich Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that their foreign ministries should quickly work
on a draft treaty defining the Caspian Sea's status, Yelstin's
press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov said he appreciated Russian oil companies' withdrawal
from a one billion dollar deal with Azerbaijan's state oil company
to develop the disputed Kyapaz offshore oil and gas field, which
Turkmenistan also claims.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Niyazov that the accord had been signed "without
consultation with the government and president" and had been since
annulled.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also agreed to resume work on a joint
Russian-Turkmen gas company and to cooperate closely in the world
gas market.
</P>
<P>
The countries bordering the Caspian Sea are divided over the
ownership of the resources in the sea, with Russia insisting five
countries share the resources and the others arguing that each
country should exploit fields lying within the waters off its coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
