<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Puts Suspected Nazi Collaborator under </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A French court in Bordeaux today
decided to put former Gaullist minister and suspected Nazi
collaborator Maurice Papon under judicial control, in preparation
for his trial which will begin on October 8.
</P>
<P>
Papon was accused of "crimes against humanity" by
collaborating with German Nazis in deporting 1,560 Jews --
including many children -- to Nazi death camps, when he was
secretary general of the Gironde prefecture under the Vichy
collaboration regime from 1942 to 1944.
</P>
<P>
Under the measure which is aimed at preventing him from
escaping, Papon was forbidden to leave France, was ordered to hand
over his identity card and passport, and was ordered to pre-inform
his destinations before traveling out of Paris.
</P>
<P>
The request to put Papon under judicial control was first
presented by the lawyer of the Association of the Sons and
Daughters of the Deported Jews of France, Arno Klarsfeld, and was
supported by the public prosecutor of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
Papon will be the second Frenchman to be tried for crimes
against humanity after former Lyon militia chief Paul Touvier was
convicted of the crime in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
