<HEADLINE> Group of 21 Reiterates Proposal for Establishment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 21 non-aligned countries
restated here today a proposal for the establishment of a negotiating
committee on nuclear disarmament within the Conference on Disarmament
(CD).
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the group at the CD plenary, Ejoh Abuah,
representative of Nigeria, said the non-aligned countries placed the
highest priority on the issue of nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
They regretted that its proposals on June 5, 1997 for an ad hoc
committee on nuclear disarmament had been rejected out of hand as
inappropriate by certain delegations, he added.
</P>
<P>
In those proposals, the group recalled its suggestion for the
re-establishment of ad hoc committees on the prevention of an arms
race in outer space and on effective international arrangements to
assure non-nuclear-weapon states against the use or threat of use
of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Certain delegations had asked for time to obtain instructions from
their competent authorities in that regard," Abuah said. "The group
would now wish to be able to benefit from those instructions, which
should have been received by now, so that work on those committees
could go forward."
</P>
<P>
The call for the establishment of an ad hoc committee on nuclear
disarmament was echoed by representatives of Cameroon and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The CD is yet to find agreement on a program of work for its 1997
session. It will have another plenary on August 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
