<HEADLINE> Attorney General: Open Mind on Immigration Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno Thursday said she would at least keep an open mind when she
reads a commission's recommendation to abolish the Immigration and
Naturalization Service (INS) and reassign its functions to other
agencies.
</P>
<P>
But Reno said her natural inclination works against "taking
things apart."
</P>
<P>
The report containing the recommendation by the U.S. Commission
on Immigration Reform is due out next month.
</P>
<P>
At her weekly news conference in the Justice Department, Reno
said, "We will obviously keep an open mind..."
</P>
<P>
"My sense is...that things don't get solved by taking them
apart and putting them back together again, she added.
</P>
<P>
Reno said INS has done "an incredible job with limited
resources," adding, "at the same time, we need to read the
report."
</P>
<P>
Reno intends to look carefully at the commission's
recommendations and will not dismiss them out of hand, according
to department officials.
</P>
<P>
Republican lawmakers have criticized INS with regard to its
efforts to protect U.S. borders and keep illegal aliens out of the
country. But Administration officials have defended progress at
INS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
