<HEADLINE> Mandela Criticises Strike by Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today criticised teachers going on a strike for
salary increase, saying he appreciated their concerns but did not
believe in action that disputed schooling.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks at a media briefing after a two-hour
meeting with the Federation of Unions of South Africa (FEDUSA) in
Northcliff, Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of members of the South African Democratic
Teachers Union (SADTU) began a two-day nationwide strike on
Wednesday, demanding for a salary increase of up to nine percent.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said: "I would have expected them to appreciate the
problems of the government. We have been in government for three
years and have been working on improving the education system."
</P>
<P>
It was just unfortunate that a section of teachers believe
they can just press for demands without appreciating what the
government has been doing, he said.
</P>
<P>
He praised FEDUSA for it playing a pivotal role in building
the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
SADTU has threatened to ballot its 160,000 members for an
indefinite strike unless the government approved a nine percent
salary increase for teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
