<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Hails U.N. Authorization of Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- France today hailed the
authorization by the United Nations Security Council allowing six
African states to continue a peace-keeping operation in the
Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council authorized on Wednesday the
continuation of the peace-keeping mission being conducted by
Burkina Faso, Gabon, Mali, Chad, Senegal and Togo in Bangui, the
capital of the Central African Republic which has been troubled by
a series of mutinies over the past one year.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also authorized these countries and
France, which is providing logistical support to them, to resort
to the use of force to ensure the security and freedom of movement
of their personnel.
</P>
<P>
"The experience of the MISAB shows the determining role that
the African capacities can play to benefit peace," said French
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Created in January 1997, the peace-keeping operation, formally
called Inter-African Mission of the Bangui Agreements (MISAB), is
aimed at helping restore peace in Central African Republic, and
supervising the surrender of arms by the former mutineers.
</P>
<P>
"In this spirit, France, in close collaboration with Britain
and the United States, puts into place a partnership (with MISAB
participants) aimed at reinforcing, in terms of training and
logistics, the capacities of the African countries," said the
French Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
France announced last week the closure of the Bouar military
base in the Central African Republic, and plans to gradually
withdraw the rest of its 1,400 troops stationed in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
