<HEADLINE> Cyprus Talks to Resume in Switzerland on August 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of two Cypriot communities
will resume their face-to-face talks on August 11 in a Swiss town,
according to a press release issued today by the United Nation
Office at Geneva (UNOG).
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus talks under the auspices of the United Nations were
opened by UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan on July 9 in Troutbeck,
New York. The talks between the leader of the Greek Cypriot
community, Glafkos Clerides, and the leader of the Turkish Cypriot
community, Rauf Denktash, are aimed at achieving a peaceful
solution to the Cyprus problem. The objective is for the parties
to craft new constitutional and institutional structures which
would allow the people of both Cypriot communities to live
together in peace.
</P>
<P>
The talks in Glion-sur-Montreux, about 100 kilometers east of
Geneva, are the second round in that process. In a statement to
the press on July 14, the Special Adviser of the Secretary-General
on Cyprus, Diego Cordovez, said that he expected that the second
phase would be a "defining moment". Cordovez said that the leaders
had taken back to Cyprus for discussion suggestions about the
modalities for a sustained negotiating process, which would begin
after the elections in Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
