<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Continue Export of Arms: Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will continue
its arms deals with Middle East countries, Defense Minister Joe
Modise said in a press conference in Pretoria today.
</P>
<P>
Joe Modise said South Africa was in danger of losing two major
arms deals because details about the countries involved had been
published in the media.
</P>
<P>
A local newspaper last weekend reported that South Africa's
state-owned arms manufacturer, Denel, was finalizing a major
contract for the sale of sophisticated artillery pieces and
anti-aircraft systems to a Middle East country.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, the newspaper ignored an interdict obtained by
Denel to prohibit the paper from publishing the name of the
country involved. According to the newspaper, the country is
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he intended to visit the client countries in
a bid to save the deals.
</P>
<P>
Asked which countries he was referring to, he said: "I will
not confirm anything. Enough damage has been done."
</P>
<P>
Modise said he felt ashamed that client confidentiality had
been broken in South Africa, adding he feared the countries
involved might decide to refuse him a visa.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa might lose billions of Rand and thousands of job
opportunities as a result," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Denel's Acting Managing Director Seshi Chongo told the press
today that last year his company generated a turn-over of 666
million U.S. Dollars. It showed a net profit of 84.2 million U.S.
Dollars, of which 22.2 million was declared as dividend in favor
of the state, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the company's exports accounted for 30 percent of its
revenue, compared with 16 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Export markets are therefore critical to Denel's business, and
the company hoped to expand its international market by 20
percent a year, said the director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
