<HEADLINE> France Deplores "Association" Between Turkey, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- France today deplored the signing
of an "association agreement" by Turkey and the self-declared
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which calls for the
partial integration of northern Cyprus into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"We think that the association agreement signed by Turkey and
the representatives of the Turkish community of Cyprus goes
against the efforts deployed in the search for a negotiated
solution," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into two parts after Turkish troops invaded
the island in 1974 following a coup d'etat in Nicosia staged by
Greek Cypriot nationalists supported by Greece.
</P>
<P>
"France wishes the reunification of Cyprus in the framework of
a federation uniting two regions and two communities, in
conformity with the resolutions of the United Nations Security
Council," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of Greek Cypriots and Turkish Cypriots will
begin meeting in Switzerland next week to find a solution to the
division of the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
