<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Air Traffic Controllers End Go-Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Air traffic controllers in
Kenya's main airports ended their five-day go-slow this morning
after reaching an agreement with the government.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is back to normal. We have explained what the
government is trying to do and they (controllers) have understood
and cooperated," Kenyan Labor Minister Philip Masinde told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
He failed to reveal details of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The air traffic controllers started their go-slow at midnight
on Friday in the capital Nairobi, the Indian Ocean port of
Mombasa, Kisumu ashore Lake Victoria and Malindi, 125 kilometers
north of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
However, the controllers here were quoted by a local source as
saying that they were assured that a report on their working
conditions had been presented to President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
The controllers asked the authorities to raise their monthly
pay by 50 folds from about 90 U.S. Dollars to almost 5,000
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
"They are asking too enormous a figure," and their demand thus
can not be met by the government, a senior official at Nairobi's
Jomo Kenyatta International Airport told Xinhua on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official also denied any relation between the go-slow of
the airport staff and the national strike set for Friday, saying
Kenyan airport staff launch go-slow almost every year. The
lastest one lasted also just a few days in December, 1996.
</P>
<P>
During the go-slow, flights into Kenya were delayed in the sky
for one to two hours before they were allowed to land. Departing
flights had been delayed for anywhere between three and 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that about 40 airlines use Kenyan airports,
bringing the country millions of Dollars in annual revenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
