<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Hits Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Shilling hit a record
low against the U.S. Dollar today, a day before the planned
nationwide strike called by the opposition for pressing for
constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling was down 4.08 percent from Wednesday to close at
a commercial average of 70.26 to the dollar today. The closing
rate on Wednesday stood at 67.50.
</P>
<P>
A new round of violence is widely predicted in the eastern
African country tomorrow as the government has already announced
illegal the strike.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling has lost 18.08 percent against the dollar since
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) announced last Thursday the
suspension of its 215-million-dollar aid package to Kenya, citing
the country's high-level corruption.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) Governor Micah Cheserem expressed
deep concern on shilling's rapid depreciation on Wednesday,
saying his bank will intervene in the foreign exchange market
whenever the need arises,
</P>
<P>
Several importers were rushing to pay their foreign bills in
order to minimize exchange losses while exporters were holding
back Dollars in anticipation of further shilling losses, he said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Cheserem noted that foreign investors in government treasury
bills and stocks were in the market following the IMF move,
buying foreign exchange to repatriate their investments.
</P>
<P>
The combination of the above forces has caused the current
turbulence in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
