<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Raises Interest Rates to 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain raised official interest
rates to 7 percent from 6.75 percent today in a bid to put the
economy on track for achieving the inflation target of 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth rate rise since the Bank of England was
empowered by the Labor government in May to determine monetary
policy. The increase puts rates at their highest level for more
than four years.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that the strong pound was putting severe
pressure on exporters and the rampant consumer spending would lead
to a resurgence in inflation.
</P>
<P>
Britain's gross domestic product grew an annual 3.4 percent in
the second quarter, a level which most economists believe cannot
be sustained for long without higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
But the British trade unions said the rate rise could put jobs
at risk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
