<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Civilian Casualties amid Escalation in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- One civilian was killed and 16
others were wounded in Israeli bombardment at south Lebanese
villages today, in response to Katyusha attacks at northern Israel
overnight.
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery focused the bombardment at Iglim Al-Toffah,
a ridge some 60 kilometers southeast of Beirut, which is often
used by guerrillas of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God,
to launch attacks on the Israeli occupation forces in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The official Lebanon News Agency (LNA) reported that more than
30 shells hit Kfar Melki, killing a villager and wounded 13 others
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Three people in Joun were also injured when their village was
showered by 35 155mm shells fired by Israeli troops in a hilltop
position overlooking the village, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
More than two dozens of houses were damaged in today's
bombardment which came after Hezbollah guerrillas fired volleys
of Katyusha rockets and mortar shells at Israeli positions in the
so-called "security zone."
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio claimed this morning that more than 10 Katyusha
rockets and mortar shells landed in the Galilee panhandle in
northern Israel without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
The LNA also quoted security sources in the border strip as
saying that a mother and her two children were killed, and a
fourth person was wounded, in the explosion of a roadside bomb at
Markaba inside the buffer zone self-carved by Israel in 1985.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Beirut, Sheikh Nabil Qawoq,
Hezbollah's senior officer responsible for affairs in the south,
accused Israel of behinding the Markaba accident, adding that his
party was committed to protecting civilians, especially in the
occupied areas.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the five-nation committee overseeing
the implementation of a cease-fire agreement between Lebanon and
Israel indefinitely postponed a meeting, which had been scheduled
to be held today at the south Lebanese border town of Naqoura.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the
United States had planned to hold the meeting to look into
three complaints filed by Lebanon over Israeli bombardment at
Lebanese villages earlier this week in which two civilians were
killed and nine others wounded, and another complaint lodged by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was postponed after five servicemen, an Irish and
four Italians, of the U.N. peacekeeping forces died when their
helicopter on a routine flight crashed inside the border strip
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The south Lebanon-based U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL)
suspended flights of all its helicopters following the incident,
making it impossible for the Lebanese and Syrian delegates to
reach Naqoura to attend the monitoring committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the helicopter crash, Lebanese Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz told reporters that "this incident should draw the
world's attention to the pains which Lebanon is suffering from
the Israeli occupation in the south and to the high price which
Lebanon and the international community is paying as a result of
this occupation."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the current escalation in south Lebanon
"expresses the stalemate caused by (Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin) Netanyahu and his country after ruining the peace
process." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
