<HEADLINE> N.Ireland Unionists, Sinn Fein to Debate on TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Spokesmen for Sinn Fein and the
Ulster Unionist Party are to hold a live debate on British TV for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
UUP security spokesman Ken Maginnies and Sinn Fein negotiator
Martin McGuiness will face each other on BBC2's Newsnight
programs next Tuesday, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
It will bring together the two adversary parties in Northern
Ireland who have been sharply critical of each other for much of
the past three decades and who have yet to sit at the same
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The pro-British UUP decided last month to take part in
television debates with Sinn Fein, IRA's political wing, because
UUP officials feared that they were losing a propaganda war
against their long-time foes by refusing direct talks with them.
</P>
<P>
Irish Republican Army, which has been fighting against the
British rule of Northern Ireland, called a ceasefire on July 20,
which allows Sinn Fein to take part in the multi-party peace talks
scheduled next month.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein wants the peace talks to start dismantling British
rule of Northern Ireland. But the British government says this can
only happen if a majority of people in the province, currently 60
percent pro-British, voted for it.
</P>
<P>
The UUP, which is opposed to have direct talks with Sinn Fein,
wants guarantees that the IRA will start surrendering arms when
the peace talks begin on September 15 because UUP does not want to
negotiate with Sinn Fein under military threat of the IRA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
