<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Largest Insurer Raises Fund for Pensions Payback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Prudential Corporation, Britain's
biggest insurer, has raised its provision of paying compensation
to 720 million US dollars for pensions misselling in an effort to
hasten the review.
</P>
<P>
The move follows pressure on the pensions industry from the
government to make faster progress in clearing up the mis-selling
scandal, which has dragged on for several years.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Prudential yesterday follows a warning from
the Association of British Insurers that compensation and other
costs from mis-selling are likely to exceed 6.4 billion US
dollars, partly because of the recent Budget's abolition of tax
credits for pension schemes.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is now offering guarantees that misselling
victims will not suffer any financial loss on retirement, nor will
they have to prove that they were missold a pension.
</P>
<P>
Sir Peter Davis, Prudential's chief executive, said: "We just
want to get the whole thing sorted out." Prudential has dealt with
16,000 compensation claims from a total of 60,000 priority cases.
</P>
<P>
Critics attacked the Prudential for hiding behind
technicalities to avoid paying up and Sir Peter admitted there had
been a change of heart last night.
</P>
<P>
He said: "There has been a shift in thinking. All of us feel
that the issue is a big one. This is overhanging the industry...We
have a lot of people working on it."
</P>
<P>
Only last month the Prudential was still arguing that it was
not liable for much of the compensation critics said it owed
customers.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the event, economic observers here said, it was
only after the scandal came to light, the corporation tried to
shift responsibility for the way people were persuaded to move
from occupational pensions into personal pensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bagach Loses Gold After Positive Doping Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Aleksandr Bagach of Ukraine, who won
the men's shot put gold medal here on five days ago, was stripped of
his world title due to positive doping test at the 6th World Athletics
Championships Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Also failed in the doping tests were men's 400m hurdler Pascal
Maran of France and women's triple jumper Oxana Zelinskaya of
Kazakhstan. Maran and Zelinskaya didn't enter the finals here.
</P>
<P>
The three athletes have tested positive for taking the stimulant
ephedrine, according to a laboratory analysis announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent decision by the IAAF Congress, these athletes
will be issued a public warning and disqualified from the competition.
</P>
<P>
The results they achieved at the current championships have been
cancelled. As a consequence of this, the revised medal placings for
the men's shot put are John Godina of the United States (gold),
Oliver-Sven Buder of Germany (silver), and C. J. Hunter of the United
States (bronze). 
</P>
</TEXT>
