<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Major Step to Curb Crimes in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's cabinet, in
response to strong appeals to stop rampant crimes in the country,
has approved a draft legislation, which will prevent hardened
criminals from obtaining bail.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed bail law approved on Wednesday, courts
will refuse bail to unsentenced prisoners previously convicted of
serious offense, like murder, rape and armed robbery, etc.
</P>
<P>
Courts will also be entitled to cancel bail if it is
discovered that the accused was previously convicted of serious
offense. In addition, judges will have the right to refuse bail
where it appears that the release of a suspect will undermine
public peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Describing this as a very tough measure, South African Justice
Minister Dullah Omar said the bill will "make a dramatic impact
on the hearing of bail applications".
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which abolished apartheid system in 1994, has
been a country where increasing crime has become a very serious
social problem.
</P>
<P>
Murderers, robbers and rapists often take advantage of the
lenient bail law to avoid legal punishment, thus having resulted
in public complaints and no confidence in the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet's go-ahead to the new bail law has apparently won
comprehensive support from all walks of life, including
opposition parties, who describe it as "an improvement of
judicial system".
</P>
<P>
However, while expressing welcome to the draft legislation,
many people are not satisfied with the simple change on the bail
issue, stressing that more urgent steps are essential to the
fight against crime.
</P>
<P>
A comment by "The Citizen" daily pointed out that "tougher
bail laws are not in themselves the final answer" to curbing
crimes.
</P>
<P>
The article urged the ruling African National Congress to bow
to public opinion over death penalty, noting that as death
penalty is an effective weapon to deter evil crimes, it must be
reintroduced.
</P>
<P>
Some legal experts pointed out that crime in South Africa has
become so serious that simply changing the law would not fully
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Martin Schonteich, parliament analyst for the South African
Institute of Race Relations, warned that criminal justice system
in the country as a whole is disintegrating due to lack of
resources, staffing and training.
</P>
<P>
Most detectives have no specialized training while 25 percent
of the policemen are functionally illiterate, he said, adding
that evil crimes cannot be controlled unless the deficiencies are
overcome. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-07 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Appoints Head of Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Bashir
today issued a republican decree, appointing Rayak Mashar as
chairman of the coordination council of southern Sudan (southern
government).
</P>
<P>
Mashar was sworn in here today in the presence of the Sudanese
president. The appointment of a deputy chairman and other council
members will follow soon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after the swearing-in ceremony,
Mashar said that legislative councils (parliaments) of Sudan's 10
southern states will be formed.
</P>
<P>
These legislative councils, he said, will elect the heads of
the southern states. Subsequently, governments of the southern
states will be instituted, and governors of the various states
appointed.
</P>
<P>
Mashar said that the four-year transition period of southern
Sudan will begin once the 23-member coordination council is
appointed.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the functions of the council during the
transition period primarily call for the establishment of peace,
prevalence of security and stability in southern Sudan, and
reconstruction, rehabilitation and development of the war-torn
territories.
</P>
<P>
Mashar appealed to John Garang, leader of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), to join the peace process, saying that
negotiations with Garang remain the only possible option.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government signed a peace agreement with four
small southern rebel factions on April 21 this year in a bid to
put an end to the 13-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPLA, the largest anti-government group operating
in southern Sudan, refused to sign the accord, creating
uncertainty over whether the peace can be holding.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's rebels in the south have fought the government since
1983, seeking a greater say in Sudan's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mashar joined the Garang movement in 1983, but quit the
movement in 1991 to form his own separate movement.
</P>
<P>
In April 1997, he signed with the Bashir government the
Khartoum peace agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
