<HEADLINE> Tunisia, Kuwait Sign Agreement for Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Tunisia and Kuwait signed an
agreement on cooperation in the field of petroleum here today, the
Tunisian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Kuwait will contribute to the construction
of a 125-kilometer pipeline that extends from Sidi Kilani oil
fields to Al Sukheira port in the southern Tunisian province of
Sfax.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a total cost of 12.2 million Tunisian dinars
(about 12 million U.S. dollars), will be completed in one
year. The pipeline will have the capacity of transporting 25,000
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Tunisian Minister of Industry
Slaheddine Bouguerra and the visiting Kuwaiti Oil Minister Issa
Mohammed Al-Mazidi.
</P>
<P>
Sidi Kilani oil fields produced some 800,000 barrels of oil in
1996. It is the third largest oil fields in Tunisia after Birma
and Ashtirt oil fields.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti oil minister arrived here Wednesday on a three-day
working visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
