<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Militia Captures Junta Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The military group of Sierra
Leone's traditional hunters, known as Kamajors, said today they
have ambushed a truck, seizing a batch of arms, ammunition and
armed guards of the junta who seized power in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors have been fighting the military junta led by
Major Johnny Koroma and its allies, the ex-rebel group of
Revolutionary United Front (RUF), since the coup.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kamajor leadership, fighting is continuing
around the southeastern Sierra Leone town of Zemin after the
junta sent reinforcement of men and artillery to the area six
miles west of the Liberian border.
</P>
<P>
The arms captured on a road leading to Zemin include 50 AK47
rifles, four cartons of ammunition, 50 rounds of anti-aircraft
mortar shells and a large number of hand grenades, said a Kamajor
regional coordinator, quoted by the British Broadcasting Company.
</P>
<P>
He said the arms were captured Wednesday evening when a truck
believed to be part of the junta's reinforcement was ambushed.
</P>
<P>
The weapons gave the Kamajors a good opportunity to properly
arm themselves for the on-going battle with Koroma's Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council (AFRC) and RUF, the Kamajor spokesman
noted.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to use the arms collected from the so-called
People's Army in Freetown to battle them out," he said, adding
that up to now his forces has advanced beyond Zemin and begun
attacking other positions of the AFRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
