<HEADLINE> Latvian New Cabinet Supported by Sejm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The new Latvian coalition
government today enjoyed confidence of the Sejm that passed a
vote, according to a report from Riga, Latvia.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass said that in the new cabinet which replaced the
Andris Skele cabinet resigned on July 28, Guntars Krasts, 39, has
become prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Krasts, who was economics minister in the former cabinet,
represents the Fatherland and Freedom national-conservative party
that recently merged with the Latvian National Independence
Movement.
</P>
<P>
From the 18 former ministers only five were dismissed from
theirs posts. Three ministers sacked by Skele for violating
anti-corruption law have not been recalled to their posts.
</P>
<P>
It was said that an exception was made for Vilis Kristopans,
railways minister, whose performance was favorably commented on.
The Skele cabinet fell because of a conflict with the parties that
aggravated after dismissals of the ministers they had nominated.
</P>
<P>
The new government was backed by 73 deputies, while 13 voted
against and three were absent.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet formed by four major factions of the Sejm will
work till the autumn of 1998 when parliamentary elections will be
held.
</P>
<P>
Krasts, the new premier, made assurances that the government
will go on with reforms and will preserve previous priorities in
executive authorities' activity.
</P>
<P>
The new coalition government in a declaration said that it
intends to continue establishing good-neighborly relations with
Russia and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
The document signed by four major parliament factions outlined
the program of the cabinet's activity. It is planned to balance
a budget, to rein in inflation at a level not above nine percent,
to complete privatization in the summer of next year and so on.
</P>
<P>
Latvia's entry into the European Union and NATO remains top
priority in the foreign policy area. It is planned to strengthen
ties with these organizations, to prepare armed forces for the
participation in the military alliance, and to ensure that Latvia
has diplomatic missions in every EU member-country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
