<HEADLINE> Justice Department Awards New Grants for Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Justice Department is
awarding 92 million dollars in new grants for The Community
Oriented Policing Services Program (COPS) to put 1,300 new
officers on the streets in communities across the country.
</P>
<P>
The COPS program, part of the 1994 Crime Act, is designed to
put 100,000 new officers on the streets by the turn of the
century, and so far has subsidized 63,000.
</P>
<P>
Of the grants announced on Thursday, more than 21.6 million
dollars, goes to Florida communities to fund 195 full-time
officers, and one part-time officer.
</P>
<P>
California communities are getting about 9.6 million dollars,
Illinois communities 7.7 million dollars for 128 full-time
officers.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 other states are also getting their shares of grants
for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The hiring program pays three-fourths of the total salary and
benefits for each officer hired for three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
