<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Spacecraft Succesfully Docks with Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Soyuz TM-26 spacecraft
with cosmonauts Anatoly Solovyov and Pavel Vinogradov on board
docked with the Mir space station at 9:02 p.m. Moscow time
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax quoted an official in the mission control center
at Korolyov outside the Moscow as saying that the docking was
carried out on automatic pilot.
</P>
<P>
The two cosmonauts will stay over six months in Mir and will
make at least six space walks, mainly to examine and repair the
Spektr research module pierced in the June 25 crash, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The first spacewalk scheduled on August 30 will be to reconnect
the cables of Spektr's solar panels to the station's power system,
which is now deprived of about 30 percent of the normal power
supply. They will examine Spektr September 3.
</P>
<P>
American astronaut David Wolf will arrive at Mir in
mid-September to replace Michael Foale and carry out research
under a Russian-U.S. program until January 1998. He may join the
repair work, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
France's Leopold Eyharts, a European space Agency astronaut,
will join the Mir crew in February 1998. He will stay in Mir for
nearly three weeks and return to Earth with Solovyov and
Vinogradov.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Russian cosmonauts Vasily Tsibliyev and
Alexander Lazutkin, currently aboard Mir, are expected to return
to the Earth August 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
