<HEADLINE> Sudan: 400 Rebels Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 400 rebels were killed in
fierce fightings with government forces in southern Sudan over the
past few days, said a military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
There was also a large seizure of ammunition including two
tanks from the largest rebel group of the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), Sudanese army spokesman General Mohmaed Al
Sattus Ahmed was quoted by the official Sudan News agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that the government forces also destroyed
SPLA's three German-made trucks full of weapons and ammunition,
and five armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA initiated its war against the Sudanese government in
1983 with the aim of achieving independence in the south.
</P>
<P>
It refused to sign and acknowledge the peace agreement which
the government and six other opposition factions signed in
Khartoum last April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
