<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Allen Johnson Caps Men's 110m Hurdles World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion and Olympic gold
medallist Allen Johnson of the United States set a world best time
this year to win the men's 110-meter hurdles gold medal at the 6th
World Athletics Championships here today.
</P>
<P>
His winning time was 12.93 seconds, the third fastest all time and
only 0.02 seconds outside the world record.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Colin Jackson of Britain clocked his best time
this year to wind up second in 13.05, and Igor Kovac of Slovakia
snatched the bronze in 13.18. The top five finishers registered their
best times of the year in the final.
</P>
<P>
Johnson bolted off the blocks fast and hit the front at the mid-way
of the race. Jackson chased him as hard as he could, but his good
technique was no match against Johnson's blistering speed.
</P>
<P>
"I just wanted to make sure I was out of the blocks ahead of
Jackson, so that he could not disturb my rhythym," said the American
winner.
</P>
<P>
"After the semifinal I was dehydrated and I drank a lot during the
night. Today I felt rejuvenated. then while warming up, I knew I would
achieve an exceptional time," added Johnson.
</P>
<P>
Jackson, who had not competed good for 18 months, was satisfied
with his result, saying:"I thought I might have enough for the gold
medal, but anyway this was the time and place for my top performance.
</P>
<P>
"I'm back to my best and Allen is at his best. A few more weeks of
training and we could have a great head to head battle, and that maybe
crack the world record," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Announces Further Actions on Burma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
announced further actions on Burma, mainly selective economic
measures.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government is withdrawing Burma's general
preferential tariff eligibility and placing Burma on the area
control list, which requires all exports from Canada to Burma to
have an export permit.
</P>
<P>
"These measures underscores Canada's concern over the
deteriorating human rights situation in Burma and are intended to
encourage the military region to enter into meaningful political
dialogue with the leaders of the democracy movement," the
government said in a new release.
</P>
<P>
With these actions, Canada joins the United States and European
Union in imposing selective economic measures against Burma.
</P>
<P>
It also urges the Canadian business community to refrain from
entering into further investment agreements or commercial ventures
in Burma.
</P>
<P>
Canada has previously cut off military sales, suspended
bilateral aid and diplomatic presence in the Asian country.
</P>
</TEXT>
