<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Abolish Obsolete Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa National
Defense Force (SANDF) will clear away excess stock of old
weapons, including anti-aircraft arms, infantry vehicles and
helicopters, Defense Minister Joe Modise said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was recently made by the Council of Defense which
includes Modise.
</P>
<P>
Modise said although the military would put an end to obsolete
weapons, nothing would be done to undermine national security.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever equipment we do away with, we have to make sure that
there is equipment to take its place so as to ensure South Africa
remains protected all the time," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Only an adequately protected South Africa can be one of the
major players in the defense of our region and the territorial
waters of our country," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Modise also noted that there are growing pressures on South
Africa to play a role in peace-keeping in other countries.
</P>
