<HEADLINE> Striking Steamsters, UPS Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The striking Teamsters union
and the United Parcel Service resumed talks today, the fourth day
of walkout that involves more than 185,000 union members through
out the United States.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to a request by Federal Mediation and
Conciliation Service Director John Calhoun Wells to meet, and
talks began around 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
Teamsters President Ron Carey said he was willing to bargain
all weekend, but questioned whether the company was ready to
negotiate seriously on issues important to the union.
</P>
<P>
UPS chief executive officer James P. Kelly said he was
"perplexed" that the union had refused to let its members vote on
the company's proposal.
</P>
<P>
The two parties face unresolved issues, including pay and
benefits, the company's use of part-time workers and pensions.
</P>
<P>
"UPS remains committed to its final contract offer and is
encouraging the union leaders to let UPS Teamsters vote on the
proposal," the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Teamster President Ron Carey said that if UPS was unwilling to
negotiate big changes to its offer, there could be no contract.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen no sign that the company has changed its
attitude, so we are not particularly optimistic about these new
talks," Carey said late on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The union blamed the strike on the company's refusal to create
thousands of full-time jobs each year from part-time positions and
to stop handing union work to outside suppliers. Between 120,000
and 130,000 union-represented workers are part-time.
</P>
<P>
But UPS said the real issue was the Teamsters' refusal to let
the company withdraw from a pension plan that includes 30 other
companies. It said with its own pension program, it would save
money in the long run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
