<HEADLINE> Egyptian PM Urges Israel to Lift "Collective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri urged here today Israel to lift a "collective
punishment" it imposed on the Palestinians following last week's
suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters upon his arrival at the Beirut Airport,
Ganzouri said "the collective punishment" will only lead to more
violence rather than solution of problems.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the Jerusalem suicide bombings in which 15
people were killed and 170 others wounded, Israel has closed the
Palestinian self-ruled areas of the West Bank and Gaza strip and
imposed crippling economic sanctions upon them.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli collective punishment practiced in the
Palestinian case could not resolve the problems, but will lead to
the increase of violence," the Egyptian prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that in order to pave the way for a resumption of the
peace talks, "Israel must totally and immediately review the
collective punishment on the Palestinian people in the past few
days."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Israeli government should also reconsider
its policy on Jewish settlements because of which the peace
negotiations were suspended last March.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian premier added that the Middle East situations
were not a problem of Egypt, nor a problem of Lebanon and all
the Arab states, but had become a "regional international
problem" and "it was not a secret that the Jewish settlements
had become an obstacle to the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri arrived here today for a two-day official visit to
Lebanon, during which he and his Lebanese counterpart Rafik
Al-Hariri will preside meetings of the Lebanese-Egyptian Highest
Joint Council.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri spoke highly of achievements made by Hariri's
government in rebuilding its country, noting that Lebanon "is
returning to a natural situation."
</P>
<P>
Hariri, on the other hand, welcomed his Egyptian counterpart's
"historical" visit, and expressed appreciation for the support
Egypt has extended to Lebanon since President Hosni Mubarak came
to power.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Ganzouri's visit will contribute in
consolidating the friendly ties between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
