<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Defends Its Anti-drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today rejected the
dissatisfaction by the United States with its efforts in drug
control, saying it is uncalled for and beyond the lines of its
recent efforts.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Musa Bamaiyi, chairman of the National Drug Law
Enforcement Agency (NDLEA), said Nigeria has been "doing well in
the drug war" and achievements have been made since 1994.
</P>
<P>
But the United States is keen on the past, particularly in the
period of 1991 to 1993, the reported high time that drug
traffickers actively used Nigeria for drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
"What is currently taking place, from 1994, they close their
eyes against it. They don't want to see," Bamaiyi said.
</P>
<P>
"It is common knowledge globally that Nigeria is doing well in
the drug war," he said, adding that the country should otherwise
be commended.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said the United States, the biggest drug market
in the world, should look at its own serious situation instead of
criticizing other countries.
</P>
<P>
The performance of NDLEA has been evident as an increasing
number of foreigners were caught with drugs in the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest edition of NDLEA's magazine "Drug
Salvation Force", nine foreigners were arrested between January
and June this year, compared to four in the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
A total of 26 foreigners were captured between January 1996 to
June this year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Of the foreigners arrested, Ghana tops the list with 13,
followed by Benin with four and Togo with two, while Lebanon,
Guinea, Liberia, India, France, Netherlands and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea recorded one person each.
</P>
<P>
According to the magazine, the quantity of seized drug has
reduced, adding while 264.54 kg of drug was found on the four
foreigners arrested last year, only 33.29 kg was discovered on
the nine arrested so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The magazine disclosed that the majority of the arrests were
made at Nigeria's land borders which, it said, had become the
favorite routes for drug traffickers in the west African
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
With the increasing removal of all restrictions on free
movement of persons and goods in the sub-region, more traffickers
would be likely to shift to the land routes, it noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
