<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Pakistan Discuss Situation in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish and Pakistani leaders
today called for a peace solution to conflicts in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz held talks with Pakistani
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayup Khan, who arrived here earlier today
on a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Yilmaz said that Turkey and Pakistan should
coordinate closely in finding a peaceful settlement to the Afghan
issue.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Ayup Khan said that Pakistan, as a neighboring
state of Afghanistan, has an advantage to hold dialogs with all
waring parties in the country, but added that Islamabad "favors
none of the clashing sides in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
Noting that Pakistan intends to hold a U.N.-supervised
international conference on the Afghanistan plight, Ayup Khan said
that Pakistan would keep Ankara very well informed on this
development.
</P>
<P>
Although there is a traditionally friendly relationship between
the two Muslim nations, Turkey and Pakistan hold opposite views on
the settlement of the Afghanistan problem.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been supporting Uzbek Militia General Rasit Dostum,
who fled to Ankara after his headquarters in Mazar-e-Sharif fell
to the Afghan Islamic militia Taliban in May.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, however, has long been known as a major supporter of
the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Calling Pakistan a friendly nation of Turkey, Yilmaz expressed
his hope that the two countries will further expand their
relations in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani foreign minister also said his government hopes
more Turkish businessmen to invest in Pakistan, a country with a
bright prospect of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman and Foreign Minister Ismail Cem also
met the visiting Pakistani foreign minister and entourage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
