<HEADLINE> IMF Meeting to Discuss Financing Package for Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today said it will convene a meeting of some interested
countries and multilateral institutions in Tokyo on August 11 to
discuss a financing package for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In view of the recent economic situation in Thailand, the IMF
sent a team to Bangkok to help map out an economic policy package
and work with the Thai authorities to further develop it into a
multi-year adjustment program that can be supported by IMF
resources.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, managing director of the IMF, issued a
statement Tuesday expressing his welcome for Thailand's policy
package which was aimed at overcoming present economic problems in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"The economic package is rightly focused on immediate and
sweeping measures aimed at assuring the solvency and strength of
Thailand's financial system and on supporting fiscal measures and
other welcome initiatives aimed at re-establishing a strong
macroeconomic basis for stability and growth of the economy,"
Camdessus said. "I found particularly appropriate the adoption of
a comprehensive restructuring of troubled financial institutions,
as this is essential to lay the basis for the re-establishment of
a sound financial sector and to set the stage for effective
recovery," he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also expressed his confidence that the strong
actions taken by Thailand Tuesday and the financial support that
could be extended to it will decisively contribute to stability in
financial markets in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo meeting is called in a bid to invite a number of
industrial nations and other international institutions to take
part in a financing package for Thailand to support the
stabilization program now being discussed with the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
