<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief Hails Albright's Statement on Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdul Meguid said he "followed with interest" the statement by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright that calls on Israel
not to take unilateral measures.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said he has seen many positive points in the comments
made by Albright Wednesday, who had largely been criticized for
aloofness to the Mideast peace-making since she took office early
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader expressed his hope that Albright's expected
tour of the region will "seriously" push forward the peace process
on the Palestinian track as well as the Syrian and Lebanese tracks
in order to defuse the explosive situation and achieve a just and
comprehensive peace for all the peoples of the region.
</P>
<P>
Albright called on in Wednesday's statement both the Israelis
and Palestinians to do more to advance the Mideast peace process
and said she may travel to the region by the end of the month if
there is "progress on the security issue."
</P>
<P>
Meguid condemned all acts of violence and cleared the
responsibility of the Palestinian National Authority for these
acts.
</P>
<P>
"The hardline Israeli stance as well as Israeli provocative
measures in Jerusalem and Arab occupied lands are the direct
reasons behind them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks which had been deadlocked since
March over Israel's construction of a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem suffered another fatal blow when the July 30 twin
suicide bombings killed 15 people in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A strongly-worded communique issued after an emergency meeting
of the Arab League Tuesday said Israel's failure to abide by the
peace agreements with the Palestinians has invited violence to the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is sending its envoy to the Mideast Dennis Ross back
to the area for talks this weekend in a bid to defuse the
tension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
