<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Police Transfers, Mere Routine: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Police Force said
today that the recent transfers of some 98 senior officers out of
Lagos were mere routine and should not be interpreted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
The police, like all institutions, transferred its officers
when necessary and should not be construed to mean anything else,
said Young Arebamen, the force's public relations officer.
</P>
<P>
In a major reorganization earlier this week, more than 1,500
senior police officers were transferred by the Force
Headquarters, with all the affected officers in the south
deployed to various northern states and their counterparts in the
north asked to report in the south.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that those sent on transfer had spent not less
than four years in the south, while others were being moved out
because of the re-location of force headquarters to the capital
Abuja in the center of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the police, worried by accusations that its
officers are unrepentantly corrupt, have set up a special task
force to rid the organization of bad eggs.
</P>
<P>
Arebamen, who is also a deputy commissioner of police, said
the task force would also arrest and prosecute those who
"corrupt' police officers by offering them bribes.
</P>
<P>
According to him, hundreds of motorists had been arrested
across the country in the last one week for giving money to
policemen to avoid being asked to produce their vehicle
documents.
</P>
<P>
Urging the public not to ridicule the police, Arebamen said
the police were the only institution in the country that did not
protect its corrupt members and that people who wanted to help
should do so with positive criticism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
