<HEADLINE> French Minister Reaffirms Policy of No Arms Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard reaffirmed today that France is committed to its policy of
no arms sale to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no new sale of French armaments to Taiwan,"
said Richard during an interview with Radio-Television Luxembourg
(RTL).
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry also reaffirmed twice in June that
France sticks to the 1994 joint communique with China, in which
Paris promised not to sell arms to Taiwan from then on.
</P>
<P>
France sold 60 Mirage-2000-5 combat aircraft to Taiwan in 1993
at a value of 3.8 billion U.S. dollars. This paralyzed Sino-French
relations for one year.
</P>
<P>
During his state visit to China in May, President Jacques
Chirac affirmed that France would honor his promise on no arms
sale to Taiwan. 
</P>
