<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Scholar On Religious Freedom in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Members and scholars of the Tibetan
Autonomous Regional Academy of Social Sciences today expressed
indignations over the unfounded accusations on the religious
situations in China included in a recent US State Department
report on religion.
</P>
<P>
At a forum organized by the academy, the scholars pointed out
that Tibetan people can prove whether Chinese people enjoy
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
They shared the view that religion is experiencing a golden age
in Tibet which has 1,781 lamaseries and temples, 300 more than all
religious venues before Tibet was liberated by peaceful means in
1951.
</P>
<P>
The number of monks and nuns in Tibet is estimated at 46,000
but the actual figure is larger. It is a common sight that
pilgrims are walking in groups on almost all the main roads in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The scholars said that the central government has taken
effective measures to promote religious development in the region,
including allocating over 300 million yuan to finance renovation
of temples and lamaseries and open them to the public.
</P>
<P>
To train scholars for Tibetan Buddhism and promote local
religion, the autonomous regional government invested heavily in
building a research institute on Tibetan Buddhism, as well as a
printing house for sacred scripts.
</P>
<P>
As for the political rights of the people from the religious
community, the scholars said that these people account for 15
percent of all the members of the Standing Committee of
the Regional People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, all cities and counties in Tibet have set up their
own religious organizations or societies. Over 600 religious
people hold positions in local people's congress, people's
political consultative conference or Buddhism Associations at all
levels.
</P>
<P>
If people come to Tibet and see religious situation here with
their own eyes, they would disagree with the irresponsible
comments made by the US report on China's religious
freedom, the scholars noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Enjoy Improved Living Standards (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese people are leading a
far better life than only a few years ago, with most citizens
enjoying a higher income level, abundant and less expensive
consumer goods, improved living conditions and access to at least
a modicum of luxuries.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita income for urban residents reached 4,300
yuan in 1996, up 3.3 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita income of rural residents hit 1,900
yuan, a rise of nine percent on 1995.
</P>
<P>
Only two decades ago, an ordinary worker earned a mere 40-50
yuan monthly, with most rural residents living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping, the architect of China's reform and opening in
1982, questioned: "How can this be cited as an advantage of
socialism...especially since we have engaged in revolution for
decades and have practiced socialism for more than 30 years?"
</P>
<P>
After China's reform and opening scored monumental achievements
during the 1979-1988 period, Deng confirmed that "the living
standards of the Chinese citizens should gradually rise on the
basis of increased production."
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, who also serves as general
secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China, told delegates attending the 14th CPC National Congress in
1992 that "ensuring a relatively comfortable life for one-fifth of
the world's population living in our country will represent an
extraordinary achievement."
</P>
<P>
The living standards of both urban and rural residents have
improved greatly in recent years due to booming production and the
accumulation of social assets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Enjoy Improved Living Standards (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fact that supplies of many products have exceeded demand
since 1994 has created a burgeoning consumer's market.
</P>
<P>
While grain and clothing coupons were commonplace during the
14th CPC National Congress, related coupon's are now nothing more
than collectors items.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Engel Index for China's urban residents fell
to below 50 percent shortly after the end of the 14th Congress
indicated that the urban residents were able to spend more than
half their income for items other than food.
</P>
<P>
Economists point to related progress as being highly
significant in the history of the daily consumption habits of the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Engel Index for urban residents hit 48.6 percent, and
the goal for the year 2000 has been set at 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, Bank savings jumped to slightly over 3.85
trillion yuan, up some 886 billion yuan on the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese can now afford color TV's and
domestically-produced appliances on their monthly salary, and most
envision the time when they will be able to purchase personal
computers or automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Statistics through the end of 1996 show that each 1,000
households owned 935 television sets, 116 air-conditioners and 342
gas water heaters.
</P>
<P>
The per capita living space in rural areas at the end of 1996
stood at 21.7 sq.m., with the 8.4 sq.m. space for urban residents
representing a 1.7 sq.m. jump on 1990.
</P>
<P>
China's intensified efforts to help impoverished people escape
poverty over the past five years have attracted wide-ranging
international attention.
</P>
<P>
While seven million Chinese people escaped poverty in 1996, the
nation's poverty-stricken population dropped to about 58
million. China's rural poverty-stricken population currently
account for less than 20 percent of the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
The current number of college students per 100,000 Chinese
citizens stands at 247, a significant rise on the 186 student
figure for 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Russia Win Openers at World Volleyball Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Olympic silver-medalists China and
fourth placers from the Atlanta Games Russia won their respective
matches on the opening day at the three-day World Women's
Volleyball Grand Prix here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
China won over Italy 3-0 (15-6, 15-6, 15-11) and Russia beat
the United States 3-0 (15-1, 15-8, 15-3).
</P>
<P>
The taller Chinese won the opening set without any problem,
with veteran spiker Wang Ziling gaining one point after another
for her side.
</P>
<P>
The second set almost went the same way, as Chinese continued
their triumphant advance with powerfulspikes and successful
blocking.
</P>
<P>
The Italians fought fearlessly in face of tough opponents, but
lack of spiking power obviously cost them the game, as they lost
the third set 15-11 and the match three sets to null.
</P>
<P>
The Americans, who finished a poorly seventh at last year's
Olympic Games in Atlanta, seemed to be paying prices for their
recent reshuffle which resulted in a brand-new line-up here. 10
out of the 12-strong American players are newcomers to be led by
only two Olympians from the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The Russians fielded the main body of its Olympic line-up here,
with three of the players standing at 1.90 meters. Their superior
height helped the team in making both effective spikes and
blocking.
</P>
<P>
And inexperienced Americans made too many unforced errors in
today's game -- nine in the first set and at least the same figure
in the second.
</P>
<P>
The Russians formed a solid defense throughout the game, which
was not much foiled even in face of powerful jump-serves launched
by some American players. The third and final set came out
totally lopsided in favor of the Russians.
</P>
<P>
Lang Ping, head coach of the Chinese team, said that her
players performed normally today and of course they had some weak
points to improve in the later competitions.
</P>
<P>
As for the fluctuation in the third set, she explained that
might be the result of fielding some newcomers. "It's normal in
any competitions like this, anyway," she said.
</P>
<P>
Italy takes on Russia and China faces United States on Saturday
and, on the event's third and final day on Sunday, Italy meets the
United States and China takes on Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
