<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriots Visit Southern Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 400 Turkish Cypriots in
Turkish-controlled northern part of the island today came to the
southern government-controlled village of Kokkina to pay homage to
those killed there 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash also visited the area by
helicopter, while other Turkish Cypriots traveled by bus.
</P>
<P>
Kokkina, in the northwest of the island, is a Turkish Cypriot
enclave, some three miles west of the Turkish occupied areas.
</P>
<P>
Greek Cypriots living in the area welcomed their Turkish
Cypriot compatriots and Cypriot police officers accompanied the 18
small buses that took them to the region.
</P>
<P>
Waldemar Rokoszewski, a spokesman for U.N. Peace-Keeping Force
in Cyprus, said today that the U.N. force monitored the trip and all
ran smoothly.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the planned visit of some 600 Greek
Cypriots to the Turkish-controlled Monastery of Ayios Andreas on
August 15 will also run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of visits was agreed by Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Denktash during their meetings in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had two meetings in Nicosia last month, under
auspices of U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel, to discuss humanitarian issues and reached an agreement
on missing persons of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Last April some 450 Turkish Cypriots crossed to southern
government-controlled areas for a pilgrimage to Hala Sultan Tekke
mosque in Larnaca to hold a ceremony commemorating their
compatriots who died in intercommunal conflict in August 1964.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
in and took over the northern third of the island following
a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
People from the two sides have been prohibited to cross the
180-kilometer-long U.N.-controlled buffer zone which separates
the island into two parts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
