<HEADLINE> France Condemns Violence by Comoran Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- France today condemned the capture
of Mahmoud Ahmed Abdallah, top aide to the Comoran president, by
separatists on the Comoran island of Anjouan who want to return to
French rule.
</P>
<P>
"France condemns all acts of violence from wherever they
originate. The Comoros problem can only be resolved through
negotiation and in a peaceful way," Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yves Doutraux said.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Ahmed Abdallah, aide to President Mohamed Taki
Abdulkarim, was taken prisoner by the separatists as he was
getting out of a helicopter on Anjouan where he was due for talks
with the rebels on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
France applauded the decision by United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to send an economic and humanitarian
mission to Moroni, capital of the Indian Ocean nation, to assess
the economic situation there.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy with the very positive reaction from the
international community... to reaffirm its attachment to the
territorial integrity of the Federal Islamic Republic of the
Comoros," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Anjouan separatists, who declared the island independent
early this week, accused the central government of treating them
like animals and asked France to listen to "the cries of distress
from the people of Anjouan."
</P>
<P>
The Comoro Islands obtained independence from France in 1975,
but one of the islands of the archipelago, Mayotte, has remained
under French rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
