<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Grows by 5.9 Percent in First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore economy grew by
5.9 percent in the first half of this year, prompting the
government to revise its forecast of growth for the whole year up
to 6 to 7 percent, Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said today.
</P>
<P>
In his national day message to mark the 32nd anniversary of the
Republic of Singapore, Goh said that the Singapore economy grew by
5.9 percent in the first half of 1997, while the economy picked up
in the second quarter, growing by 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Manufacturing is recovering from the slowdown. All other
sectors did well. Reflecting our strong fundamentals, we attracted
4.8 billion US dollars of manufacturing investments in the first
half of this year," he added.
</P>
<P>
Given the better-than-expected economic performance, the
Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) expects the economy to
continue to strengthen in the second half of 1997. For the full
year, MTI has revised its growth forecast of 6 to 7 percent, the
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting globalisation and technology as the two "major
driving forces" behind the fast changing world, Goh said that the
government will make efforts to equip the Singaporean people with
useful skills, such as Information Technology (IT) skills,
thinking skills and learning skills.
</P>
<P>
"We will go beyond the schools, to create in our society a
culture of lifelong learning and training. Our people must also
have the spirit of innovation, adventure and entrepreneurship," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
