<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK New Airport Expected to Open Next April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new international
airport and its related facilities are expected to open in April
next year as scheduled, a local government official said today.
</P>
<P>
In a report circulated here tonight, Billy Lam, director of the
New Airport Projects Coordination Office (NAPCO), said a total of
85 percent of the Airport Core Program (ACP) had been completed by
the end of June. Now, the works directly funded by the government
are close to completion, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are all working toward the target of opening the new
airport in April next year and the airport railway shortly after,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lam, the budgetary cost accounting for the program
is 156.4 billion Hong Kong dollars (about 20.2 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
NAPCO has been working closely with the Airport Authority and
the MTR (metro) Corporation to ensure that the airport and the
railway will, as with the government ACP works, be completed on
time and within the budget, the NAPCO director said.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the ACP projects at Chek Lap Kok, one of
the world's largest infrastructure programs, was designed to
provide modern, efficient air transport facilities, together with
associated road and rail facilities and new land, that will
support Hong Kong's continued expansion well into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and British governments signed a memorandum of
understanding in 1991, noting the "urgent need for a new airport
in Hong Kong" and requiring the Hong Kong government to complete
the ACP projects "to the maximum extent possible" by June 30,
1997.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the ACP projects started soon after the
memorandum was signed and the local government is responsible for
seven of the 10 ACP projects, which cover land reclamation and the
construction of highways and a new town near the new airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
