<HEADLINE> Nepalese Women Act Against Liquor, Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Women of a village in
Kanchanpur district of far-western Nepal once again rose up
against their drunk husbands and intensified a campaign against
liquor and gambling, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
A group of women in Tribhuvan Basti Village recently handed
four drunk husbands over to the police for legal action, the
reports said.
These women also demonstrated against what they called
"unscrupulous people" engaged in bootlegging, gambling, women
trafficking and smuggling, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
They also formed various kinds of resistance groups to push
forward their campaign.
</P>
<P>
An anti-liquor group recently destroyed 11,000 rupees (about
193 U.S. dollars) worth of home-brewed liquor.
</P>
<P>
A pressure group was also formed to levy fines on those who
defy the liquor ban, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
An anti-gamble group also acted by slapping fines of 501 rupees
(about 8.8 dollars) on persons playing host to gambling and 301
rupees (about 5.2 dollars) on those engaged, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Cases of wives being ill-treated by their drunk husbands are
not rare in Nepal, especially in rural areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
