<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Parties Agree on Ambassadors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Presidency today
reached agreement on the allocation of ambassadorships among
the country's three ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
But they failed to agree on other provisions of joint
statehood, such as passports, citizenship and opening airports,
together with currency and flag.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement on ambassadors, 13 of Bosnia's
ambassadorial posts will go to Muslims, 11 to Serbs and nine to
Croats.
</P>
<P>
Of the most contested posts, the ambassador to the United
Nations will be nominated by the chairman of the presidency,
Muslim Alija Izetbegovic, the Washington post by the Serb member
of the presidency, Momcilo Krajisnik, and the Tokyo post by Croat
member Kresimir Zubak.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached early this morning after a marathon
14-hour meeting of the presidency attended by a U.S. delegation
led by the former assistant secretary of state, Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, who brokered the Dayton peace accord which ended the
Bosnian war at the end of 1995, flew to Bosnia after the
presidency failed to meet the August 1 deadline for agreements on
statehood issues.
</P>
<P>
The presidency also reached agreement on the formation of a
permanent military committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the committee will be composed of the
three members of the presidency, a representative of each one
and the chiefs of the general staff and defense ministers of the
Serb Republic and the Muslim-Croat Federation.
</P>
<P>
Meetings of the committee will be presided over by
representatives of the two entities in turn and the venues will
also be chosen in turn.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed on a single country code for Bosnia's
telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Coal Mines Enhance Profitability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China's major state-owned coal
mines reversed losses and earned profits in the first six months
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Coal Industry attributes the breakthrough to
extensive efforts to expand structural reform, strengthen
management, reduce redundancies, and control both raw coal
production and storage, as well as to rectifying production order
and placing priority on safety.
</P>
<P>
Major state coal mines earned over 110 million yuan in profit
during the first six months. But, these mines lost more than 300
million yuan during the same period of last year. Fifty-seven
state-owned coal producers, or 61.3 percent of the total, are
currently earning profits.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the first six months of the year show that the
country's total raw coal output fell by 2.15 percent to 620.76
million tons, down 13.63 million tons when compared to the 1996
period. Production at major state coal mines for the period fell
by 1.25 percent to 256.38 million tons of raw coal, down 3.25
million tons.
</P>
<P>
End of June figures show the country had coal stockpiles of
73.72 million tons, down 23.93 million tons on January figures,
with large state coal mines recording stockpiles of 31.97 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
Mines have laid off 188,000 workers, with some 106,000 of them
having found reemployment after completing retraining courses.
</P>
<P>
Major mines achieved a record mechanization rate of 72.73
percent and a production efficiency of 2.01 person tons/day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Events Since Last Party National Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua New Agency today released
the second part of a retrospective article by the Communist Party
of China Central Committee Party Literature Research Center
covering the major events which have taken place since July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The events include the milestone Sixth Plenary Session of the
14th CPC Central Committee in October 1996. The Session adopted
the CPC Central Committee's Resolution on Important Issues
Concerning the Promotion of Ethical and Cultural Progress.
</P>
<P>
The plenum pointed out that a socialist society is one making
progress in all aspects and the socialist modernization drive
constitutes a course that scores coordinated development of both
material progress and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
The ethical progress China is advocating is the one focusing on
economic construction and based on the four cardinal principles as
well as the policy of the reform and open-up. It embodies the fine
tradition of the Chinese nation while reflecting features of the
times, and is based on China and oriented with the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
It is an arduous historical mission for the Chinese Communist
Party and the Chinese people to promote ethical and cultural
progress under the condition of creating a market economy and
opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The article also listed following major events;
</P>
<P>
-- On November 12, 1996, Liu Huaqing inspected PLA troops to be
stationed in Hong Kong. Liu, vice chairman of the Central Military
Commission, asked the troops to strictly discipline themselves and
set a good image by forging friendly relationships with Hong Kong
residents, in addition to performing their military duties.
</P>
<P>
-- On December 11, 1996, the First Selection Committee of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region held the third plenary
meeting, during which Tung Chee-hua was elected one of the
candidates for the position of the HKSAR Chief Executive. On
December 16, Premier Li Peng signed a State Council decree,
appointing Tung the first HKSAR Chief Executive. On December 21,
the Selection Committee held the fourth plenary meeting to elect
members of the HKSAR Provisional Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
-- On January 29, 1997, President Jiang Zemin made a speech at
the Eighth Plenary Session of the CPC Central Commission for
Disciplinary inspection, calling on the whole Party to carry forward
the spirit of hard work.
</P>
<P>
-- On February 19, 1997, Deng Xiaoping passed away. The Central
Committee of the Chinese Communist Party, the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress, the State Council, the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference and the Central
Military Commission jointly released the letter to the whole
Party, the whole army and the entire Chinese People.
</P>
<P>
On February 25, the memorial meeting for Deng Xiaoping was held
at the Great Hall of the People. In his memorial speech, Jiang
Zemin gave high credits to Deng and his great contributions and
urged the whole Party and the whole nation to carry on Deng's
will and push forward the great cause of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
-- During March 1-14, 1997, the Eighth National People's
Congress held the fifth session. In his government report, Premier
Li Peng said China's economic growth in 1996 was characterized by
rapid development and a substantial drop in inflation.
</P>
<P>
-- On June 30, 1997, President Jiang Zemin ordered the PLA
troops to advance to the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
and to carry out their duties at zero hour on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Chinese government delegation headed by
President Jiang Zemin arrived in Hong Kong to attend the handover
ceremony. This was the first time that a top Chinese leader ever
set foot on this part of the Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
At mid-night of July 1, the handover ceremony was held in Hong
Kong, followed by the inauguration of the HKSAR and HKSAR
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
