<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- The effort by China, the United States and the two Koreas to
set up peace talks aimed at formally ending the Korean War broke
off after failing to resolve differences over which topics those
talks would cover, including the 37,000 American troops in South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
-- Israel and the Palestinians said they welcomed a new
American initiative unveiled by Secretary of State Madeleine K.
Albright on Wednesday, but they also presented rival views of
priorities under the plan. The Israelis want the Palestinians to
crack down on terrorists while the Palestinians want Israel to
ease up on pressure tactics.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Four years after the discovery of the defective gene that
causes Huntington's disease, researchers have produced the first
clues about how the gene causes the devastating disorder.
</P>
<P>
-- The Senate Committee examining campaign finance abuses has
begun an investigation to determine whether the Democratic
National Committee obstructed the panel's inquiry by not
delivering until Monday 4,000 pages of documents from the files of
former DNC Finance Director Richard Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. avoided a trade battle with the 15-nation European
Union by agreeing to change a controversial law that required
Italian and French designers to put a "Made in China" label on many
of their expensive silk goods.
</P>
<P>
-- Thailand's tough measures to deal with its battered economy
have received the blessings of the Clinton administration, the
International Monetary Fund and Japan, but they are certainly not
generating any enthusiasm in Thailand itself. 
</P>
