<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Jobless Rate Down Slightly in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The unemployment rate in Canada
dipped 0.1 percentage points in July to 9.0 percent, Statistics
Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Since February, the rate has dropped 0.7 percentage points and
is now at its lowest level since 1990, the federal statistics
agency noted.
</P>
<P>
In July, Canada's employment edged up slightly by an estimated
15,000. Some 222,000 more jobs has been created across the country
in the past five months.
</P>
<P>
Private sector has contributed the most to Canada's improved
labor force picture. It has created 152,000 more jobs for paid
employees and 75,000 for the self-employed since February.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, employment in the public sector has seen little
change during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Job gains in July were in the service sector, led by an
increase of 32,000 in retail trade.
</P>
<P>
While employment in the service sector has been edging up in
recent months, the growth in July is the only large increase since
last November.
</P>
<P>
In July, employment in utilities rose by 6,000, bringing gains
over the past two months to 9,000.
</P>
<P>
Construction employment fell by 12,000 in July, offsetting the
gain observed in June. Manufacturing employment also fell in
July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
