<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Socioeconomic Development During 1992-1996 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved major advances
in socioeconomic development since the 14th National Congress of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) was held in 1992.
</P>
<P>
A recent State Statistics Bureau (SSB) survey shows that gross
domestic product (GDP) has reached 6.78 trillion yuan, an increase
of 77.1 percent over the 1991 figure in real terms.
</P>
<P>
Thus the annual GDP increment stood at 12.1 percent over the
past five years. Such a growth rate represents one of the world's
most rapidly developing economies, and is also the highest one
since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
China has fulfilled economic development target five years
ahead of the central government's schedule, which was settled in
the beginning of 1980s and outlined a four-fold rise on 1980 GDP
figures by the end of century.
</P>
<P>
World Bank statistics indicate that China's 1996 GDP figures
ranked seventh in the world, up from the 10th place ranking in
1991.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's major supplier of grain, cotton, edible
oil, meat, eggs, textiles, coal, steel and cement, with the nation
ranking second in terms of power generation, fertilizer and
chemical fibers, and fifth in crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that China successfully readjusted its
economic structure during the 1992-1996 period, while at the same
time maintaining stable agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
The nation's secondary and tertiary industries have generated
80 percent of GDP, up 4.5 percentage points from 1991.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the emphasis on large-scale investments in fixed
assets since 1992 has further improved the nation's infrastructure
and forces of production, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Socioeconomic Development during 1992-1996 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The report also showed that China pumped 8.12 trillion yuan
into the fixed assets between 1992-1996 period, up an average 32.6
percent annually. The funds were used to complete 299,000
infrastructure and 218,000 technical renovation projects.
</P>
<P>
China has recorded two consecutive years of good grain
harvests, with output for the animal husbandry and fisheries
sectors growing on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Steel output exceeded 100 million tons in 1996, up 30 percent
from 1991. In addition, the output of raw coal climbed to 1.38
billion tons, and power generation surpassed 1,000 billion kw-hr..
</P>
<P>
SSB statistics also indicate a high growth rate for the auto
manufacturing, household electric appliance, computer,
telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
The economic upsurge has also led to stable improvements in
living standards, with 1996 per capita earnings of urban residents
reaching 4,377 yuan, up 41.6 percent on 1991 figure when
considering inflationary factors.
</P>
<P>
The average income of rural residents has jumped 28.8 percent
on 1991 figures to 1,926 yuan, registering an average annual
growth rate of 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the 1992-1996 period, the sales of consumer goods have
grown by 11 percent annually. In the five years, the amount of the
sales of consumer goods reached 8.37 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Savings deposits have increased by nearly three trillion yuan,
with 1996 year-end totals hitting 3.85 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, indices for health, nutrition, life expectancy and
primary school education have either approached or exceeded levels
in "medium-level developed nations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges End of Cold War Mentality in Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China today called for the
abandonment of Cold War mentality in U.N. human rights bodies.
</P>
<P>
The most challenging task facing the United Nations human
rights bodies now is to seek ways of doing away with Cold War
mentality, Wu Jianmin, head of China's observer delegation, told a
session of the Sub-Commission on the Prevention of Discrimination
and Protection of Minorities under the U.N. Human Rights
Commission.
</P>
<P>
He called on the experts of the sub-commission, the
"think-tank" for the U.N. human rights program, to come forward
with new ideas and new thinking in place of the Cold War mentality
in order that substantial progress can be made in the cause of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 185 member states of the United Nations is
different from the other in many ways, Wu said. Yet, in spite of
all the differences, many common grounds and interests between
nations exist.
</P>
<P>
"The typical feature of the Cold War mentality is to focus on
the differences," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"To those who stick to this kind of mentality, their values,
their concept of human rights, their views and approaches to the
human rights question are the gospels of the world. Any opinions
differing from theirs invites their open condemnation,
name-calling, even willful sanctions."
</P>
<P>
Consequently, Wu said, since the end of the Cold War in 1991,
"What we have seen is nothing but the aggravation of mutual
antagonism with the human rights cause as the ultimate loser."
</P>
<P>
"We should concentrate on the common grounds and interests
instead of differences," Wu suggested. "We should stop
finger-pointing and start exchanging our experience in the
promotion of human rights."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the cause of human rights can only be
advanced by developing cooperation on the basis of common
interests.
</P>
<P>
He said the most fundamental human right is subsistence.
</P>
<P>
"Protection of the basic human rights means first and foremost
the guarantee of the survival of a human being. This is common
sense," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. statistics, 1.3 billion people, or 23 percent
of the world's population, live below the poverty line, he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
"If we can discuss these issues of human rights and share
experience with each other in order to find possible solutions,
and if we can help enable more people each year to enjoy the most
fundamental human right -- freedom from hunger -- through our
efforts, won't it be our most convincing achievement in promoting
human rights?" he asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Corrupt Beijing Senior Officials Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Two high-ranking Beijing
officials have received prison terms for their participation
in acts of bribery.
</P>
<P>
Tie Ying, former vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Beijing Municipal People's Congress, was sentenced to 15 years
imprisonment and denied her political rights for a period of
three years.
</P>
<P>
Tie was convicted of accepting bribes worth 430,000 yuan
(US$52,000) between 1992-1995, when she served as the
secretary-general and director of the General Office of the
Beijing municipal government, and director of the Beijing
Municipal Legal Affairs Office.
</P>
<P>
She was also expelled from the Communist Party of China (CPC)
and relieved of all official posts.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court
confiscated all her illegally obtained funds and property.
</P>
<P>
Tie, 66, did not file an appeal to the higher court.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jicheng, 66, former vice-chairman of the Beijing
Municipal Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), was convicted of illegally accepting goods
valued at 220,000 yuan during the 1992-1994 period, when he served
as the director of the Beijing Municipal Construction
Administrative Committee, and mayor assistant. Huang was
removed from his post and expelled from the CPC.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the Beijing Higher People's Court rejected Huang's
appeal for a 10-year prison sentence and two years deprivation of
his political rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
