<HEADLINE> France "Deeply Worried" About Tension in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is "deeply
worried" by the escalating tension in southern Lebanon, as a series
of tit-for-tat attacks have been going on between Israeli troops and
the Hezbollah guerrillas for a few days which have killed at least
five people.
</P>
<P>
"We deplore profoundly that the civilian victims were attacked
several times, by both sides of the Israeli-Lebanese frontier. We
appeal to all the parties for the greatest restraint," said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
The truce monitoring committee consisting of France, the United
States, Israel, Syria and Lebanon will meet on Sunday to examine the
complaints presented by Israel and Lebanon on the violations of the
ceasefire understanding signed in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel should spare civilians in southern
Lebanon from violence, while the Hezbollah should stop attacking
northern Israel with rockets.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have been breaking the truce agreement for days in
tit-for-tat attacks upon each other around Israel's self-declared
"security zone" in southern Lebanon, after Israel launched commando
and bombing raids beyond the security zone against Hezbollah
targets.
</P>
<P>
Three rockets landed this morning in a village in northern Israel,
slighting wounding a woman and damaging a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for an Israeli village to be attacked
since the "Grapes of Wrath" operation launched by Israel in April
1996, which killed 170 Lebanese civilians and caused hundreds of
thousands to flee the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
