<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's First Half Current Account Surplus Up 40 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
rose 40.4 percent to 5.05 trillion yen (42.8 billion U.S. dollars)
in the first half of this year over the same period in 1996, the
Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The rise, the first since the first half of 1993, reflected
strong exports of automobile and office equipment, including
personal computers, the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
It also reflected a fall in the deficit in services.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 15 percent to 24 trillion yen (204.1
billion dollars), rising for the sixth straight half-year
period. Imports rose 13.8 percent to 18.9 trillion yen (160.2
billion dollars), also rising for the sixth successive half-year
period.
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade surplus increased 20 percent to 5.18
trillion yen (43.9 billion dollars), also the first rise since
1993. But the services trade, including tourism, registered a
deficit of 3.2 trillion yen (27.1 billion dollars), down
marginally over 1996.
</P>
<P>
That translated into a surplus in goods and services of 1.98
trillion yen (16.8 billion dollars), 77 percent more than the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry officials say that the surplus will not
continue this rate of growth in the medium to long term, but
economists here are sceptical, predicting that this rate of
expansion will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
