<HEADLINE> Saddam Calls on Iran to Develop Bilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
today called upon Iran to pursue a policy of cooperation,
stabilization of relations and development of bilateral ties on
the genuine and clear basis.
</P>
<P>
Saddam issued the call in his address on the occasion of the
lapse of nine years after the end of the Iraqi-Iranian war,
according to the Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Saddam demanded the release of Iraqi prisoners of war held in
Iran and the return of Iraqi properties, including civil and
military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
He said that this was a prerequisite for regional stability,
mutual respect and balanced interests.
</P>
<P>
Saddam made the appeal right after new Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami assumed office last Sunday. Khatami has
expressed Iran's intention to develop relations with other
countries, particularly with countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi president, however, affirmed that "unless a policy
of cooperation and good intentions is pursued by Iran, we will
not be attracted by mere changes of headlines or the replacement
of one person by another or one party for the other."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Iranian war lasted for eight years, from 1980 to
1988. One of the most serious residues of this war is the issue
of prisoners of war and those missing-in-action. It constitutes
the prime obstacle in the face of normalization of diplomatic
and political relations between Baghdad and Tehran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
