<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Peace in S. Leone Still Out of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- There might still be a long way
towards the resolution of the Sierra Leonean crisis arising from
the May 25 coup although the military junta has expressed
intention to resume peace talks with west African countries.
</P>
<P>
Faced with increasing international pressure for restoration
of the elected government in the troubled country, the military
junta said Thursday there was still room for further negotiations
despite the failure of the Abidjan talks, according to the Armed
Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC).
</P>
<P>
AFRC is currently the highest governing body in Sierra Leone
set up after the coup that toppled the civilian government led by
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
In his address over the state radio Thursday, AFRC chairman,
self-appointed head of state, Major Johnny Koroma offered to go
back with regional mediators, saying that his plan for a
four-year transition to civil rule was "not watertight".
</P>
<P>
He said he had "initiated moves for the resumption of
negotiations" with envoys of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Four on Sierra Leone, made of foreign
ministers of Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire, have held
two rounds of talks with a delegation of the junta.
</P>
<P>
The first brought a ceasefire agreement in mid-July while the
second broke down following Koroma's announcement on July 30 of
his intention to stay in power until the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
In a swift reaction to Koroma's refusal to an immediate
step-down, ECOWAS Chairman, Nigeria's head of state, General Sani
Abacha announced "full-scale" sanctions against the junta last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, warned
Wednesday it would take reprisal to any ship and aircraft
attempting to enter Sierra Leone's territorial waters and
airspace, which it sees is in contravention of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
The warning was followed by a presidential statement of the
United Nations Security Council, expressing its readiness to
"take appropriate measures" to restore Kabbah's
democratically-elected government.
</P>
<P>
The council said the attempt by the soldiers in Sierra Leone
to set conditions for the restoration of Kabbah was
"unacceptable". It urged them to renounce their intention to
remain in power and resume negotiations with the ECOWAS Committee
of Four without delay.
</P>
<P>
While the council blamed the junta for the breakdown of the
talks held in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, for lack of good faith,
Koroma said the talks collapsed "because the ECOWAS committee
wanted to impose their mandate on the delegation" of the junta.
</P>
<P>
According to Koroma's four-year transition plan, the junta
will hand over power to a new government coming out of an
election to be organized by it at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Koroma explained in his Thursday radio address that the plan
could "form the basis for further negotiations".
</P>
<P>
Although no reaction to Koroma's explanation has been heard
from ECOWAS, or the international community, analysts noted it
goes far away from the required immediate handover.
</P>
<P>
A military source here told Xinhua today that it could be
"impossible" for the talks to be resumed on the basis of the
junta's transition plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
