<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Cultivate Ornamental Plants with Cell Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese horticulturists
successfully bred their first batch of 60,000 ornamental plants,
"green giants", by introducing the new technology of cell
splitting.
</P>
<P>
Experts, from the Liuzhou Horticulture Research Institute in
south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, took cells out of
leaves, stems or stalks, to cultivate a new breed.
</P>
<P>
A research team of the institute has worked for plant asexual
reproduction since 1988.
</P>
<P>
The new breed is growing fast and is resistant to insect pests
and diseases while keeping the characteristics of the same kind,
according to the horticulturists.
</P>
<P>
They also said the first group of ornamental plants, now some
60,000 in number, are expected to extend to 200,000 plants by the
end of this year, and that they will have a bright market future.
</P>
<P>
So far, the new breed of "green giants" have been well
received by clients in south China's Guangzhou, Foshan and
Jinchengjiang cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
