<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Evacuees Return to German Flood Area As Water Recedes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Many people who fled the worst flood of
the century in eastern Germany during the past three weeks were
allowed to return homes as water levels on the flooded Oder River
continued to recede overnight.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that they had noticed no leaky spot along the
160-kilometer dike along the Oder River which separates Germany from
Poland. Water levels were retreating at a rate of about one centimeter
per hour throughout the flooded area.
</P>
<P>
In the southern region of the Oder, people were beginning to return
as the highest state of alarm was lift on Thursday. But in the
hardest-hit Ziltendorf flatland, where several villages had been
submerged up to rooftops, floodwaters were expected to take at least
one and half weeks to retreat completely from the current level of
1.80 meters.
</P>
<P>
Further downstream in the Oderbruch region in the north, the
situation remained serious enough to keep residents from returning to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
The water mass there still went down too slowly and continued to
mount high pressure on the sodden dike. The water levels should drop
at least one meter to justify a real relaxation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
After an unprecedented mobilization of rescue materials and
manpower, Germany has managed to escape the worst of the flooding
which has claimed over 100 lives of people in Poland and the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
In the next couple of days, many of the 11,000 German soldiers
brought in for the disaster will leave the flooded region, but others
will remain to help make the area livable.
</P>
<P>
The German government has set aside 500 million German marks (270
million U.S. dollars) to pay for the flood damage and to help rebuild
the region economically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
