<HEADLINE> Biko's House to be Declared National Monument in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Slain black consciousness
leader of South Africa Steve Biko's house in King William's town
would be declared a national monument.
</P>
<P>
The local government of Eastern Cape province announced the
decision on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Biko died in police custody in September 1977 during the
apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
An official of the local government told a press conference in
King William's town that the Ginsberg cemetery in the city would
become a garden of remembrance because it was a resting place for
Biko's mentors and elders.
</P>
<P>
The press conference was attended by Biko's widow, Ntsiki,
members of the National Monument Council and councillors from
East London city and King William's town.
</P>
<P>
Ntsiki Biko said her late husband was banished to the house by
the apartheid regime. The house was now being used by her
Brother- in-law, Khaya Biko.
</P>
<P>
The East London City Council announced that Biko's statue was
to be unveiled by South African presidetn Nelson Mandela on
September 12 in front of the East London City Hall.
</P>
<P>
Steve Biko was an important member of the African National
Congress during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In 1976, an uprising by students in Soweto against the
apartheid education system spread throughout South Africa, on the
heels of a new black consciousness movement set up under Biko's
guidance to encourage black people to walk tall.
</P>
<P>
The arrest and killing of Biko in police custody created a
fresh outburst of the public anger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
