<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Salvage Arms Deal with Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise has said that he will visit the Middle East
to salvage two major arms deals with countries in the region,
which, he claimed, have been jeopardised by premature disclosure
in the media.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Business Day today quoted Modise as saying that
although he supported the concept of transparency, there were
limits to what the media should reveal.
</P>
<P>
Local mass media revealed in mid-July that South Africa
state-owned arms manufacturer Denel was trying to make a
1.6-billion U.S. dollar arms deal with a Middle East country,
believed to be Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The proposed weapons export deal, including mobile artillery
and anti-aircraft missiles, would be the biggest of its kind in
South African history, informed sources were quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the report, Modise said that the disclosure in
the media might have resulted in loss of "thousands of jobs". "I
do not think our people want to pay such a high price for
information," he said.
</P>
<P>
Modise declined to identify which country South Africa is
making arms deal with, and refused to divulge when he would start
the Mideast journey.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Denel had spent millions over many years
to promote and market its products in the Middle East. Modise had
been involved in the promotion of the deals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
