<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, U.S. to Conduct Missile Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Defense Minister Ian
McLachlan today declared a defense practice range in northwest
Western Australia for a series of surface to air missile launches
to be conducted by Australian and U.S. defense organizations next
month.
</P>
<P>
The planned launches aim to determine if the Jindalee radar can
detect missiles like the Iraqi Scuds fired during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be conducted by the Australian Defense Science
and Technology Organization and the U.S. Ballistic Missile Defense
Organization, has been named DUNDEE (down under early warning
experiment).
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the firing site was well away from any settled
areas.
</P>
<P>
He said four unarmed Terrier surface to air missiles would be
fired to splash down about 100 kilometers out to sea.
</P>
<P>
Access to the area near the launch site and impact zone will be
restricted at the time of firings, beginning in September, the
defense minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
McLachlan said the aim is to investigate possible detection of
missile launches as soon after launch as possible and several
sensors would be used to collect data.
</P>
<P>
They include satellites, the Jindalee over-the-horizon radar at
central Australia's Alice Springs and the United States' own
portable over-the-horizon radar.
</P>
<P>
"Although Australia does not face a threat from such weapons
(Scuds missiles), it is prudent that we acquire an understanding
of ballistic missile defense technologies," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Project DUNDEE is an example of the strengthening of the
alliance relationship with the U.S. under the coalition government
and will add a significant contemporary dimension to the defense
relationship," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
