<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria  Soon to Export Liquefied Petroleum Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will start exporting
liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) next week from its Escravos Gas
Project in Delta State in the south, the Daily Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the project will be able to export 8,000
barrels or 1,509 tons of LPG per day, ensuring an annual income
of 92 million U.S. dollars, while the country's total gas export
stood at 15 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Started in 1991, the Escravos Gas Project costs a total of 569
million dollars and is jointly financed by the Chevron Nigeria
Limited and the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC).
</P>
<P>
It marks the first substantial progress that Nigeria has made
in developing its rich gas resources, the majority of which is
flared into the air at various oil fields.
</P>
<P>
Much bigger than it is the 3.6-billion-dollar Nigeria
Liquefied Natural Gas Project financed by NNPC, Shell, Elf and
Agip, which is expected to be operational by 1999.
</P>
<P>
There are also the Oso Phase II Natural Gas Liquid by NNPC and
Mobil, and the Eleme Petrochemical Phase II Project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0147 </DOCNO>
