<HEADLINE> Malaysian Army to Base Air Squadron in Sarawak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian Army will
station the second squadron of its air wing in Sarawak, East
Malaysia, as part of its overall expansion and reinforcement
program of the unit by 2010, its chief Gen. Ismail Hassan said
today.
</P>
<P>
The proposed squadron would be commissioned during the Eighth
Malaysia Plan period (2001-2010), the army chief told reporters in
Kluang, about 300 kilometers southeast of here, according to the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"Its formation will enhance the air wing's support role
capability besides being an important element in increasing the
army's mobility," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ismail said the army has applied for allocations to acquire at
least 22 utility helicopters for the air wing for light
observation as personnel transporter and for emergency medical
evacuation roles.
</P>
<P>
The first squadron, set up in July 1994, now has a complement
of 17 flyers and 10 French-made Alouette helicopters.  
</P>
