<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Fund Partner Countries in Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Countries in central and eastern
Europe including some of the former Soviet republics will soon be
funded by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in their
research and development.
</P>
<P>
The aid program, announced here today by the NATO Science
Committee, is known as the "Science for Peace Program" which aims
to enable scientists in NATO partner countries to engage in
applied research and development projects as well as assist
partner countries in their transition toward market-oriented and
environmentally-sound economies.
</P>
<P>
It will also contribute to the overall stability and peace in
the whole region, a NATO press release said.
</P>
<P>
The Science for Peace projects, lasting three to five years,
will be jointly carried out among the 16 NATO members and its 28
partners. Projects involving more than one partner country will
be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
NATO money will be funneled to such sectors as research
equipment, training of project-related personnel and
project-specific consumables.
</P>
<P>
Austria, Finland, Sweden and Switzerland, however, are not to
get money from the NATO Science for Peace Program funds due to
their status of development.
</P>
<P>
The partner countries eligible for the funds include Albania,
Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic,
Estonia, Georgia, Hungary, Kazakhstan, Kyrghyzstan, Latvia,
Lithuania, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Russia, Slovakia, Slovenia,
Tajikistan, Macedonia, Turkmenistan, Ukraine and Uzbekistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Legislator Meets President Pro Tempore of US Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese top legislator Qiao Shi
said here today he hoped that President Jiang Zemin's upcoming
visit to the US scheduled for this fall will achieve the
anticipated results and open up a new era of Sino-US ties oriented
to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qiao, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC), made this remark during a
meeting today with Strom Thurmond, president pro tempore of the US
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, some positive progress has been made in
bilateral relations, with high-level exchange of visits increasing
and economic and trade co-operation advancing steadily, he said,
adding both sides are now making preparations for the visit, and
Sino-US ties are facing a good opportunity for further improvement
and development.
</P>
<P>
Qiao went on to say that China has always attached importance
to its relations with the US, and made unremitting efforts in this
regard. Although tremendous changes have taken place in the world
situation in the post-Cold War period, China and the US still
enjoy wide-ranging and important common interests, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the new historical conditions, he added, the demand of
maintaining and developing Sino-US cooperation has been kept
increasing, instead of being reduced, and there is a very great
potential for cooperation especially in their joint efforts to
safeguard world or regional peace, develop bilateral economic and
trade ties and promote the development and prosperity of the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
This is the basis for the continuous growth of Sino-US
relations and should become the common understanding of the two
countries and their people, Qiao noted.
</P>
<P>
China will never pose as a threat to the US, and at the turn of
the century, both countries should, proceeding from the need of
safeguarding the fundamental interests of the two peoples and
promoting the peace, stability and prosperity of the Asia-Pacific
region, strictly abide by the principles enshrined in the three
Sino-US joint communiques and maintain and constantly develop the
long-term stability, so as to contribute more in the new century.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Qiao gave the US visitors a briefing on the
structure and functions of the NPC as well as its legislative work.
</P>
<P>
Thurmond held that China and the US should combine efforts to
handle a number of major issues concerning trade, security, and
regional matters. Bilateral cooperation between the US and China
benefits not only the people of the two countries, but the people
of all countries in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thurmond also expressed the hope that the legislative bodies of
the two countries will enhance cooperation and dialogues, saying
this is conductive to the further development of bilateral ties.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- More than 100,000 amateurs of astronomy are gathering today
in 200 sites across France to observe the Sun, which is the theme
of this year's scientific seminar "The Seventh Night of the Stars"
organized by the French Association of Astronomy.
</P>
<P>
-- Despite the threat of catastro-physical "climatic surprise"
due to global atmospheric warming, the delegates from 170
countries meeting in Bonn this week failed to make commitment on
statistically limiting the emission of greenhouse gas by cars,
industries or heating systems.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin will decide today the
volume of spending in the 1998 budget, which is bound to cut
public deficit to 3 percent of gross domestic product in
accordance with the Maastricht treaty criteria for joining the
euro. No new credits will be granted to the key ministries such as
those of employment and education, while the budget for defense is
expected to be cut by four-five billion francs (about 630-790
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
-- Violent storms again struck France Thursday without causing
major damages. A tropical climate began to reign in the country
since the beginning of the week, causing a depression in areas
along the Atlantic coast with very hot and humid air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
