<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Lashes out at Latest U.S. Sanction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran's ex-president Akbar
Hashemi Rafsanjani today lashed out at the latest U.S. sanction,
terming it as "the declaration of psychological war against
Iran."
</P>
<P>
Addressing a large crowd of Friday prayers on the campus of
Tehran University, Rafsanjani said "the measure shows what kind
of people and what kind of power Iran is confronting."
</P>
<P>
The United States announced Thursday that it had dropped the
punishment ceiling from 40 million U.S. dollars of investment to
20 million dollars for foreign firms to invest in Iranian oil
and gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the United States passed a law to punish no-
American companies which invest 40 million dollars or more in
Iranian oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the second largest oil exporter in the world, pumps 3.6
million barrels of oil per day and exports 2.5 million barrels
of crude per day.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry is the pillar of Iran's economy. Iran earns
about 14-16 billion dollars by exporting crude oil and the oil
export revenue accounts for about 70 percent of the total export.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafsanjani, who is now chief of the State Expediency
Council, said that nothing has happened to the Iranian industry
despite the U.S. sanction in the past year. "No development
projects has been affected," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It was as if mosquito was making noise near to our ear," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Build Ethnographic Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
decided to build an ethnographic museum with a view to protecting
the country's diverse cultural identity, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The government has listed the construction of the museum in its
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1997-2002).
</P>
<P>
And land has been allocated for the museum in Champadevi, about
nine kilometers southwest of Kathmandu, capital of Nepal, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
A 21-member Nepal National Ethnographic Museum Management
Committee has also been established, including representatives
from the Sports and Culture Ministry, the Forests Ministry, the
Finance Ministry and other government departments.
</P>
<P>
Apart from preserving ancient culture and lifestyles of the 61
ethnic groups in Nepal, the proposed museum will also help
Nepalese and foreigners gain knowledge about all the ethnic groups
at one place, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of building an ethnographic museum in Nepal was
first discussed by anthropologists from the United States,
Germany, Britain, Norway, Sweden and India in Kathmandu about five
years ago, the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Recalls Ambassador to U.S. for Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has recalled its
Ambassador to the United States Benjamin Kipkorir after he tabled
a wrong document on Kenya's constitutional reforms to the U.S.
congress.
</P>
<P>
Kipkorir was recalled at the end of his tour of duty on July
31 and replaced by Samson Chemai who has headed Kenya's mission
in Japan since August 1995, the Foreign Ministry confirmed in a
statement issued last night.
</P>
<P>
In a mix-up, Kipkorir presented to a sub-committee on Africa
in the U.S. House of Representatives last Wednesday draft bills
on Kenya's constitutional reforms from an opposition parliament
member instead of bills from the government.
</P>
<P>
The wrong document, which also bore Kenyan Attorney-General
Amos Wako's name, was part of two bills drafted by the opposition
seeking the repeal of laws charged as oppressive and review of
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Reasons of such a gaffe are not available.
</P>
<P>
Disputes over constitutional reforms have become fierce in the
eastern African country. Clashes between the government and the
opposition pressing for reforms claimed 13 lives on July 7 around
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kipkorir, once the executive chairman of the Kenya Commercial
Bank, was appointed ambassador to the U.S. in March 1994. He was
also once the chief of the Institute of African Studies at the
University of Nairobi and a senior lecturer on history.
</P>
<P>
Chemai, a veteran engineer, was the Managing Director of Kenya
Posts and Telecommunication Corporation and the Director of Kenya
College of Communication Technology before he was moved into
diplomatic service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Beats China in Volleyball Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Argentina defeated
China 3-0 in a volleyball friendly in La Plata on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Argentians displayed better teamwork in the match, beating
the visitors 15-4, 15-3 and 15-9 in 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team, preparing for the Asian Volleyball
Championships next month, will meet the hosts in their second
match in Neuquen on Friday. 
