<HEADLINE> Africa Wins New Boost for 2004 Olympic Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Cape Town's 2004 Olympic
bid received a huge shot in the arm on Thursday when the African
Amateur Athletics Confederation (AAAC) unanimously endorsed a
supporting decision.
</P>
<P>
The AAAC President Lamine Diack announced the decision in
Athens, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Diack said the body supports the bid, as the continent of
Africa deserves to be recognized for its contribution to
international athletics and the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
He was flanked by Ethiopia's 10,000 meter world champion Haile
Gebrselassie and South Africa's 400 meter hurdles silver medalist
Llewellyn Herbert.
</P>
<P>
Diack said the AAAC "pledged to be part of the process to
bring the Games to Africa for the first time".
</P>
<P>
"Africa must be given the opportunity to show that the
performances of its athletes can be matched by its ability to
stage the greatest sporting show on earth," he said.
</P>
<P>
South African National Olympic Committee Thursday admits the
country's bid logo--the Olympic rings below the national flag.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee is due to announce the
host city for the 2004 Olympic game in Switzerland on September
5.
</P>
<P>
The other world cities bidding to host the game are Greek's
Athens, Brazil's Buenos Aires, Italy's Rome and Sweeden's
Stockholm. 
</P>
