<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New HIV Test Kit Developed in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A quick and cheap test kit for
the diagnosis of HIV (virus which causes AIDS) has been developed
by Kenyan and Japanese scientists in the eastern African country,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The kit, known as the Particle Agglutination HIV test (PA HIV
test), only takes some two hours to perform and costs about 60
Kenyan Shillings (around one U.S. Dollar), the scientists at the
Kenya Medical Research Institute were quoted as saying here.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the Elisa test which is widely used around the
world, the new method has a longer shelf life and does not
require sophisticated equipment or highly-skilled manpower, said
Dr. Davy Koech, the director of the institute.
</P>
<P>
The new kit thus can be used in rural health centers, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The kit has been tested on 300 samples with an accuracy of
more than 98 percent, said Koech. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
