<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Hits 2 Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker today following heavy selling by U.S. investment houses
overnight which pushed the unit down to levels not seen in just
over two years.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar hit a low of 72.93 US cents, a level not
seen since July 1995. It managed to close a little higher in
Sydney at 73.15 US cents, but down from 73.58 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Offshore players sold the currency following the release
Thursday of domestic labor force data, which showed there was
still a way to go before the jobs market improved.
</P>
<P>
The data was published amid some debate over whether the
Reserve Bank of Australia could cut the official cash rate a sixth
time, in the current economic cycle.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange traders said the risk was weighted toward some
further downside in the exchange rate in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The currency probably would hold between 72.80 and 73.30 US
cents in the near term, said John Radinoff, SBC Warburg Australian
foreign exchange executive director.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 86.57 Japanese yen from 87.15 yen
Thursday and at 1.3640 German marks from 1.3881 marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
