<HEADLINE> World Bank Continues to Provide Loans to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has reaffirmed
its commitment to finance energy projects in Kenya and expressed
its willingness to fund more projects, Kenyan Energy Minister
Kirugi M'Nyjubdua was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister told a press conference held here Thursday that
the World Bank had approved some 136 million U.S. Dollars for
energy projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the suspension of aid by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) would not directly affect the funding of
energy projects by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that "we negotiate with the World Bank and
not the IMF for project support. We have no problem with the
World Bank. We have had meetings with them and they have been
very understanding."
</P>
<P>
A World Bank mission which is on a visit to Kenya has
reaffirmed its commitment to finance energy projects. he noted.
</P>
<P>
M'Mukindia pointed out that other donors had committed funds
for power projects as a result of implementation of reforms by
his ministry.
</P>
<P>
The IMF decided on July 31 to halt the three-year Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility because of the alleged corruption
in Kenya's government departments.
</P>
<P>
IMF's loan suspension has triggered a depreciation in Kenyan
Shilling, and raised speculations that some other international
financial institutions would follow suit. 
</P>
