<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Wool Prices Drops Before Stabilizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Wool prices dropped sharply at
this week's sales before stabilizing, the Australian Council of
Wool Exporters (ACWE) said today.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern Market Indicator closed at 696 Australian cents
(508 U.S. cents) a clean kilogram, down 22 Australian cents.
</P>
<P>
"Although prices stabilized on the last day of selling, with
more widespread competition evident at the lower price basis, the
extent of the drop in prices earlier in the week surprised most
exporters," the council said in its weekly market review.
</P>
<P>
A total of 87,841 bales were offered this week, with a pass-in
rate of 16.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The council blamed continuing relatively high offerings for
this time in the season, holidays in the northern hemisphere and
an appreciating Australian dollar against European currencies for
a short-term negative impact on the market.
</P>
<P>
"There was, however, a noticeable increase in Chinese inquiry
at the lower price basis as the week progressed, particularly for
coarser micron wool."
</P>
<P>
About 100,150 bales are roistered for sale in Sydney, Adelaide
and Fremantle next week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
