<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Philippines to Address Common Problems at Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the Philippines
today agreed to take an immediate action to address the problems
of illegal activities in the Sulu Sea and upgrading communication
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the five-day fourth
Malaysia-Philippines Border Patrol Coordinating Group (BPCG)
Meeting which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian delegation was led by Rear Admiral Tuan Hashim
Tuan Mohamad, director of the Maritime Enforcement Coordinating
Center (MECC) in the Department of National Security, and the
Philippines by Commander of the Philippine Southern Command Lt-Gen
Romeo A. Padiernos.
</P>
<P>
The communication facilities and procedures were agreed to be
upgraded to ease the flow of information between the Philippines
Southern Command Headquarters in Zamboanga city and the MECC in
Lumut, Malaysia, the two delegations said at a joint news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Both sides expressed their satisfaction with the existing
cooperation, especially in carrying out joint border patrols, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Tuan Hashim said the linkages between the Southern Command and
MECC in Lumut were vital to both parties to carry out operations
more effectively and meaningfully.
</P>
<P>
Since its formation four years ago, the BPCG has been
conducting regular border patrols in the Sulu Sea, and both
countries are also involved in search and rescue activities.
</P>
<P>
The Sulu Sea has not been completely free from various illegal
activities such as robbery at sea, smuggling and destructive
fishing methods.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 37 cases of piracy and 23 cases of smuggling were
reported in the Sulu Sea while until May this year, seven cases of
piracy and 23 cases of smuggling were reported.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian delegation leader said "serious considerations
and actions should be undertaken to overcome this problem which
poses a threat to the economy and stability in this area."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and the Philippines held a joint operation
"successfully" in April. The meeting here agreed that such
operations should continue for the mutual benefit of both
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The next BPCG meeting will be held in the Philippines in April
next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
