<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Region Develops Water-saving Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, an extremely arid part of northwest China, has tried to
develop water-saving agriculture to maintain its steady economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
In addition to some large water conservation projects, there is
a leek-proof ditch 15,000 km long, an annual soil improvement
project on one million mu (about 66,700 ha), and expansion of a
0.93 million-ha irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
To help pay for this, the government has earmarked a certain
amount of cotton revenues every year for the irrigation projects
in major cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to look for investment from joint ventures and
solely-funded ventures. These efforts have brought in 400 million
yuan more annually in water-saving program.
</P>
<P>
New irrigation methods, such as trickle and spray irrigation,
have been used in Xinjiang in its attempt to become the leading
cotton producer and a major grain producer.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the program, which started in the
early 1990s, has had some success. The use of the advanced
irrigation with the trickle and spray systems has increased to 38
million mu (2.53 million ha). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0171 </DOCNO>
