<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Down Due to BHP Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed on a depressed note, dragging down at the close by troubled
blue chip resource company BHP.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said the market bellwether
had taken a big hit in trading following the announcement of BHP
Petroleum head John O'Connor's resignation just before the close.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest hit is BHP and it's reflected in the resource
stock and in the general index," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I think it now requires very serious assessment. It seems
obvious there's quite a lot of animosity building on the board."
</P>
<P>
At the close, BHP's shares were down 45 cents to 16.99
Australian dollars, continuing their market slide in the wake of
BHP minerals head Dick Carter's shock departure and the company's
review of its global assets.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil was reflected in the all ordinaries index, which
fell 6.3 to 2711.4.
</P>
<P>
Coca Cola Amatil took a toll on earlier trading with a drop in
value, but clawed its way back, closing three cents down to 16.14
Australian dollars, following yesterday's 25.6 cent decline over
analysts' concerns over the group's European interim profits.
</P>
<P>
The soft drink giant revealed on Wednesday a 69.7 percent rise
in net profit to 98.1 million Australian dollars (72.59 million
U.S. dollars) for the six months to June 30, including a 40
million Australian dollar (29.6 million U.S. dollar) net profit
from its newly acquired Philippines operations.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was up 1.6 points to 4383.8, compared
with a fall of 14.2 points to 1404.4 in the all resources index.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Rio Tinto rose 45 cents to 21.30
Australian dollars, Western Mining dropped 16 to 7.49 Australian
dollars and Woodside Petroleum dropped 23 to 11.22 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 3.8 points to 1283.6 after the precious
metal increased to 321.60 U.S. dollars in spot trading, from
318.85 U.S. dollars late last night.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector closed 12.6 points to 5174.7. ANZ dropped
eight to 10.40 Australian dollars and NAB was down three cents to
19.63 Australian dollars, while CBA was up 25 cents to 16.82
Australian dollars and Westpac rose three to 8.58 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 385.91 million shares worth 1.047 million
Australian dollars (775.41 million U.S. dollars), with rises of
511 outnumbering falls of 493.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
