<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Helps Southeast China Develop Aquatic Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and China's Fujian
province are taking advantage of their geographic proximity to
develop Fujian's aquatic sector.
</P>
<P>
To Fujian, Hong Kong is the second largest aquatic market and
an important transfer point. In 1996, some 20 percent of Fujian's
exported aquatic products were sold on the Hong Kong market or
went to other countries and regions via Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
And Fujian imports 50 million US dollars worth of aquatic
products and related products through Hong Kong annually. About
200 million young eels go to Fujian via Hong Kong every year, for
example.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has invested heavily in Fujian's aquatic sector. By
the end of 1996, there were 480 Sino-overseas joint ventures
engaged in aquatic production in Fujian, with a total investment
of 360 million US dollars, including 183 million dollars from Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has also played a unique role in ties between the
mainland and Taiwan and has introduced funds and advanced
technology from Taiwan and provided temporary storage for aquatic
products being sold to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Fujian has worked hard promoting the aquatic
industry, and aquatic output was 2.85 million tons in 1996, or
1.66 million tons more than that of 1990.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Fujian's Xiamen city signed an agreement with Hong
Kong to build a fishing port at a cost of 64 million yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
