<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Parliamentary Speaker Denies Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Speaker of the
People's Assembly (Parliament) Ahmed Fathi Sorour has denied that
he would pay a visit to Iraq to mend Arab fences, according to
Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that Sorour informed Kuwaiti Speaker of
National Assembly Ahmad Al-Saadoun during a telephone
conversation Thursday that he would not take up such a step
without notifying the parties concerned, including Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi newspaper reported Thursday that Sorour, who is
also head of the International and Arab Parliamentary Unions,
would soon visit Baghdad on a mission aimed at mediating to
improve the Arab relations soured since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Sorour told his Kuwaiti counterpart that "such reports were
baseless."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait started this year a reconciliation process with
respect to relations with countries it regarded as pro-Iraq
during the Gulf War which liberated it from Iraqi occupation.
</P>
<P>
But it refused to reconcile with Iraq under President Saddam
Hussein and as long as the issue of prisoners of war is not
solved.
</P>
<P>
Al-Saadoun said his conversations with Sorour were in line
with regular contacts with his Arab colleagues to follow up
the latest developments in the parliamentary arenas.
</P>
<P>
He again asserted the importance of a full Iraqi compliance
with the international resolutions related to its invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
