<HEADLINE> Chinese Musicians Develop Traditional Operas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Lu Xiaojie and his brother Lu
Xiaoxi in China's Jiangsu Province have just released their first
CD and cassette tape of their performance on the "erhu," a
two-string Chinese musical instrument.
</P>
<P>
The two brothers have spent a long time perfecting their skill
with this traditional instrument, and are embarked on a two-year
project to play and record all the typical songs of 100 folk opera
forms, a third of all the traditional operas in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Musicians Publishing House has helped them in this
10-CD and cassette tape exploration of their art form.
</P>
<P>
They began their performances of opera tunes on the "erhu" in
the 1960s and have put considerable effort into developing and
promoting the traditional art form over the past 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
