<HEADLINE> Kenya Lifts Ban on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has lifted
its air travel ban on Burundi and allowed Burundi to purchase
"limited amounts" of fuel from Kenya "on humanitarian grounds",
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
This came after a petition by Burundian President Pierre
Buyoya and ahead of a ministerial technical committee meeting set
for Uganda's capital Kampala next week on Burundi situation.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Assistant Minister for Foreign Affairs Sheldon Muchilwa
was quoted as saying that transport operators including U.N.
agencies are no longer required to seek clearance on flights
between Kenya and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"It is the government's view that the political situation in
the Great Lakes region has fundamentally changed and warrants a
fresh examination of the sanctions issue," said Muchilwa.
</P>
<P>
Following a regional summit on the Burundi conflict on April
16, 1997, sanctions on the tiny central African country were
eased on food, education, medicine, agricultural inputs and
construction materials.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes countries slapped economic sanctions on
Burundi last year when Buyoya wrested power from the civilian
government of former president Sylvester Ntibantunganya in a
military coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
