<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sets Bottom Line for Workers' Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Jiangsu Province in east China is
taking steps to guarantee the bottom line of the living expenses
for the workers.
</P>
<P>
The province decided in 1995 that wages employers pay to their
workers are not allowed to be lower than the local minimum wage
standard.
</P>
<P>
It then adopted a bottom-line policy and put forward three
monthly salary standards based on different jobs: 210, 175 and 140
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Now the figures have been raised to 280, 250 and 210 yuan. One
or two percent of the province's workers are benefiting from the
practice.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu began to carry out the unemployment insurance system in
the 1980s, which now have covered 6.38 million workers, accounting
for 88 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The province has raised 1.13 billion yuan of unemployment
insurance funds, and provided unemployment relief for some 200,000
workers, living subsidies for 837,000 laid-offs, and helped
440,000 find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
It began last year to provide 100-140 yuan aid to poor urban
residents, whose monthly income is lower than local minimum wage
standards. And those who lost labor ability and above 70 years old
will get 10-20 percent more. Financial departments have paid 10
million yuan to more than 70,000 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
