<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 08:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Continue its Peacekeeping Mission in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi has stressed his country's continuous commitment to
peacekeeping mission in south Lebanon despite the disastrous
helicopter crash Wednesday night, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prodi carried out a whistlestop visit in Beirut Thursday
night and held a meeting with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi in
the presence of Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, according to the
English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"I came to Lebanon to express the sorrow of the Italian
people and government for the loss of the four Italian soldiers
and the Irishman who gave their lives in the defense of peace,"
Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
The five men died when their helicopter, an Italian Bell
Augusta, of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) in which
they were serving, crashed in an Israeli-occupied border strip
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the cause of the crash had not been determined,
adding that an Italian team had joined UNIFIL experts in the
search for clues.
</P>
<P>
But he ruled out sabotage, saying that "there is no reason why
there should be such an act against the Italians."
</P>
<P>
Insisting that Rome's commitment to the peacekeeping task
remains unchanged, the premier said that "we paid a price but our
continued contribution is essential for peace. This is our duty
and we will fulfill it."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Prodi was in Israel where he paid his last respects
to the five peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
The victims' bodies, retrieved shortly after the incident
from the wreckage at At-Tiri village in the Israeli-controlled
buffer zone in south Lebanon, had been placed in coffins at Tel
Aviv's Abu Kabir forensic institute.
</P>
<P>
Recounting the incident, a UNIFIL officer was quoted as
saying that the helicopter apparently flew into the side of a
hill in the thick fog shrouding At-Tiri.
</P>
<P>
The crash has raised the number of U.N. peacekeeper's death to
214 since the 4,500-strong UNIFIL was first sent to south
Lebanon in 1978 under the U.N. Security Council Resolution
425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Fuel Prices Rise to New High in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Strengthening U.S. dollars and
weakening petroleum markets have combined to pump up the car fuel
prices in Belgium to a new high since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Within two days, the Belgian Economic Ministry twice rewrote
the price tags and motorists now have to pay 40.10 Belgian francs
(1.02 dollars) for a liter of the Super 98 gasoline (unleaded) and
42.30 francs (1.08 dollars) for the Super gasoline, 0.4 to 0.5
francs more on a liter, the newspaper La Libre Belgique reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Local economists feared that car fuel prices may rise further
as they have always done in the past decade and may even shoot to
an all-time high in the near future.
</P>
<P>
But the newspaper quoted them as saying that the chance for a
down-spinning inflation is limited.
</P>
<P>
A liter of Super 98 sold at 28.10 francs (74 cents) per liter
in July 1989 when the exchange rate was at around 38 francs for a
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate was 38.975 francs for a dollar today as
against 37.60 francs for the dollar at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian francs have been losing ground against the dollar
ever since the Mexican peso crisis in late 1994 and early 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
