<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 75 Percent of Ugandans Suffer From Goiter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- About 75 percent of Ugandan
population suffers from goiter due to lack of iodine in their
food and drinking water, local paper, The Monitor, reported
today.
</P>
<P>
According to John T. Kakitahi, an associate professor at the
Institution of Public Health, goiter causes severe brain damage
and stunted growth in children.
</P>
<P>
Kakitahi sponsored a survey with other experts in 1992 and
1996 on the theme. He said that the lack of iodine in their food
and drinking water has given rise to precocity, with girls' early
grown breasts, and boys' adult voice and dwarf bodies.
</P>
<P>
He enumerated districts of Kapchorwa in the east, Kabale and
Hoima in the west and Mubende in the center as the worst-hit
areas of goiter where the disease rate is as high as from 62 to
78 percent of the whole population.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, lack of iron also affects Ugandans. Many
miscarriages are caused by lack of iron.
</P>
<P>
He adviced Ugandans to add iodine in their salt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
