<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Income of Beijing Residents Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The majority of the residents in
Beijing are living an ever better life as their income grows.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey by the Municipal Statistics Bureau divided the
three million-plus families in Beijing into five categories based
on their 1996 income:
</P>
<P>
Poor family -- this group of families numbers 16,000, or 4.4
percent of the total. With an income less than 10,000 yuan (about
1,200 US dollars) a year, they just wish to make their ends
meet. Some of the retirees, factory layoffs, or physically
disabled people are in this group;
</P>
<P>
Families able to feed and cloth themselves -- such families
account for 10.2 percent of Beijing's total. They include
wage-earners with no other source of income. Most of them live in
suburban counties;
</P>
<P>
Families with relatively comfortable living conditions -- this
refers to families making 16,000 yuan to 35,000 yuan a year. More
than 68 percent of the households in the capital belong to this
category. Most of them work in government departments and
organizations or are employees of large state-run enterprises;
</P>
<P>
Better-off families -- they include 360,000 households, or 15
percent of the total. They consist of self-employed businessmen or
people working as senior staffers in foreign-funded companies in
Beijing. Their income range from 35,000 yuan to 100,000 yuan;
</P>
<P>
Wealthy families -- two percent of Beijing households belong to
this category which make more than 100,000 yuan a year. They are
mostly private entrepreneurs, legal persons of share-holding
companies, construction project contractors, movie stars or pop
singers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
