<HEADLINE> North China Province Preserves Ancient Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China's Shanxi province plans to
raise more money for cultural relics preservation and to increase
the number of ancient buildings being protected.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi has more than 18,400 historical sites, ancient
buildings, and cave temples. Over 9,000 of them are made of wood,
and more than a hundred were built before the 10th century. The
buildings are scattered all across the province, making the
maintenance work very difficult, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The province is a "treasure-house of Chinese ancient buildings"
and has already spent over 70 million yuan (8.75 million US
dollars) since the 1980s to preserve its historical buildings from
different dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the province has had 16 state-level and
58 province-level cultural relics preservation projects.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Research Institute for Preservation of Ancient
Buildings, with the support of many prominent experts and advanced
computer systems, has been devoting itself to the study, design,
planning, and work of most of the preservation projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
