<HEADLINE> Hangzhou to Build New Railway Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Hangzhou Railway Station,
believed to be the last old one of the kind in Chinese provincial
capitals, has been demolished to pave the way for the construction
of a new railway hub.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-two years ago, a group of local businesses collected
money to build Zhejiang province's first railway linking Hangzhou
with Ningbo and Suzhou, as well as the Hangzhou Railway Station.
</P>
<P>
The railway station was destroyed during the war years and
rebuilt in 1939.
</P>
<P>
A symbolic structure of Hangzhou during the past half century,
the railway station was inadequate to handle the increasing
passenger flows in recent years. The passenger flow at the station
was 1.324 million at the beginning of the 1950s, and the number
grew to 8.011 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new station will be a modern one, with a designed capacity
of accommodating 5,200 passengers at the peak time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
