<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wiping Out Illiteracy in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of illiterate people in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has fallen from
1949's 90 percent to four percent of the total population after
several decades of work.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region has 16 million people, 76 percent of whom
are farmers and herdsmen. As a relatively backward region in terms
of economic development, it has been praised by the State and by
the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO) in anti-illiteracy effort.
</P>
<P>
To wipe out illiteracy efforts, the regional government
allocates more than a million yuan (about 125,000 US dollars)
every year for the campaign, and laws and regulations related to
the work have been promulgated.
</P>
<P>
Technical training schools for farmers and herdsmen have also
been set up in more than 80 percent of the towns and counties in
the region. The local government has also worked hard to provide
education opportunities for school-age children, which has
successfully prevented an increase in illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the region's urban illiteracy rate has been
brought down to below two percent, lower than the state's
standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
