<HEADLINE> Peace in Angola Conducive to Regional Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The final peace in Angola will
enable the country to play a greater role in eastern and southern
Africa, an official with the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Erastus Mwencha, the acting secretary for the regional
organization, made the remark at a press conference at the end of
his four-day visit to Angola.
</P>
<P>
He said that the eastern and southern African region has a
strong desire for integration and earnestly hopes that the final
peace in Angola will be realized at an earlier date.
</P>
<P>
On his Angola tour, the official said that his visit has
achieved "positive" result and provided him with an opportunity
to know for himself that Angola has rich natural resources and a
great potential for future development, especially in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Angola should make full use of the resources for development,
he said.
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that the war in Angola has deterred the
country from fully carrying out the plan of the organization, and
forced the organization to waive its membership fees until a
final peace is materialized.
</P>
<P>
He said the Angolan entrepreneurs have a keen interest in
regional trade and so his organization will establish an
information center in the country to help them exchange
information with their regional counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The common market, he said, will send an expert delegation to
Angola to make market investigation.
</P>
<P>
The 23-member Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), founded in 1994, is an organization that has grown from
the Preferential Trade Area for Eastern and Southern Africa
(PTA). Its headquarters is located in Lusaka, Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
