<HEADLINE> Strike staged in Philippine Transport Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Transport and labor groups in the
Philippines started today a planned nationwide strike to pressure
the government to lower prices of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
In Metro Manila, the protesters took to the streets at as early
as 4 a.m. after government officials failed to persuade their
leaders to abandon the strike.
</P>
<P>
The protesters assured the public that their action would be
peaceful, but it inevitably caused serious traffic jams and had
many passengers stranded, especially in the southern part of Metro
Manila.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces and the Philippine National Police had sent
trucks to ferry trapped passengers in affected routes.
</P>
<P>
The strike did not affect Makati City, the commercial center of
the capital city, because two jeepny driver organizations in the
area had refused to join the strike.
</P>
<P>
Classes in all elementary and secondary schools had been
suspended while colleges and universities were given the option to
declare class suspension.
</P>
<P>
The police said there are so far no untoward incidents
reported. It is also unknown whether strikes were also staged in
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The country's oil prices of petroleum products went up as a
result of the recent devaluation of the Philippine peso.
</P>
