<HEADLINE> Foundation Benefits Children of Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The "Children's World"
Foundation of Shanghai, China's commercial and trade center, has
gained a reputation for itself over the past ten years for its
good results in working with children.
</P>
<P>
The non-governmental organization was started by several
prominent persons in 1987, and lists China's well-known writer, Ba
Jin, as an honorary chairman. It owns a part-time art school for
children and has 53 teaching centers for more than 6,300
students. Many of the students have won prizes in district- or
city-level art competitions.
</P>
<P>
It has helped finance five kindergartens, which have provided
an education for nearly 4,000 children in four of the city's
districts and have won several honors given by the municipal or
district government.
</P>
<P>
While the number of children in other kindergartens generally
seems to be on the decline, these five kindergartens have had to
set up five more classes. One of them is even planning to expand
by building a branch kindergarten of 1,500 square meters.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the municipal government, the foundation set
up a children's museum that has had some 200,000 visitors since it
opened in May 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
