<HEADLINE> Economic Zones Help Chinese Tourist City's Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Four economic development zones
in the scenic city of Hangzhou, the capital of China's Zhejiang
Province, are playing a big role in local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Hi-tech Industrial Development Zone, the Economic and
Technological Development Zone, the Zhejiang Tourist Zone, and the
Xiaoshan Economic and Technological Development Zone now have over
800 enterprises with foreign backing from the United States,
Japan, France, Australia and other countries, with a total of 2.1
billion US Dollars and 4.5 billion yuan in investment.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 400 have gone into operation, and generated 8.5
billion yuan in output and 1.1 billion in profits in
1996. Investment has mainly gone to textile, garment, food
processing, electronics, machinery, pharmaceutical, and tourism
industries.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that the city government's policies and
practices have helped improve the zones' investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The hi-tech development zone is the pioneer of the four. Last
year, it had 5.2 billion yuan in output value and 800 million in
profits. A third of its products were sold overseas.
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou Economic and Technological Development Zone has
been designated a satellite city for Hangzhou and has attracted
many foreign investors, with 16 multinationals, like Merck, United
Biscuits Investment PLC, and National/Panasonic having set up
shops there.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the zone reported 200 million yuan in pre-tax
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
