<HEADLINE> India's Congress Plenary Session Opens in Calcutta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALCUTTA (India), August 8 (Xinhua) -- The 80th National
Congress (I) plenary session opened at the Netaji Indoor Stadium
here today to sum up experiences in the past five years since the
last plenary session in 1992, formulate new strategies and elect
new leadership of the party.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since independence in 1947 that the
Congress party (I), who is not in power in the Center as well as
in West Bengal with Calcutta as its state capital, has convened
the current plenary session here.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Congress President and Prime Minister Indira Gandhi
organized the party's plenary session in this city.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party, the second largest party in India, lost its
general election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech here today, Congress President Sitaram
Kesri called upon party members to fight against corruption which
has lead to the party's failure in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
He said that his party would continue to support the United
Front government's economic reforms and its efforts to improve
India's relations with all countries, especially with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The current plenary session is expected to adopt political,
economic and international resolutions reflecting the party's
policies and strategies in various fields in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it will reaffirm its support to the United
Front government in the Center.
</P>
<P>
A new Congress Working Committee (CWC), the highest
policy-making body of the party, will be elected at the current
session.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 foreign party delegations including the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC) delegation headed by Ma Wenpu, vice minister
of International Liaison Department of the Central Committee of
the CPC, have been invited to attend the plenary session.
</P>
