<HEADLINE> Livestock Increasing in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region is expected to see increased output of livestock
this year, after recovering from the natural disasters at the end
of 1996, according to officials here.
</P>
<P>
A snowstorm that was one of the worst in the past 30 years hit
the region's major pastoral, destroying many houses, barns, and
some 130 million mu (8.7 million hectares) of pastureland. More
than 11 million heads of animals were affected by the storm.
</P>
<P>
But the regional government worked with herdsmen from different
ethnic groups to deal with the disaster, and spent more than 300
million yuan (about 41 million US dollars) and sent 586 million kg
of feed and 8.6 billion kg of forage grass to the
disaster-stricken area.
</P>
<P>
At present, the region ranks second in China in the number of
livestocks. More than 48 million heads of different animals were
raised in the first half of this year, an increase of about 1.2
million over the same period of 1996. Over 270,000 tons of meat
were producted in the first six months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
