<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comatose Patients Receive Special Therapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Heilongjiang Rehab Hospital
has used a combination of Western and traditional Chinese
therapies to treat 89 comatose patients.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Keven, a young college student, regained consciousness
thanks to the hospital's treatment program. Zhang recovered from a
two-month coma and walked out of the hospital with the help of
family members.
</P>
<P>
Comatose patients suffer from extended periods of paralysis
and restricted eye movement, with medical terminology for the
symptoms known as a "continuous vegetative state".
</P>
<P>
The hospital, located in Harbin, capital of northeast China's
Heilongjiang Province, has developed a series of therapies to
treat comatose patients. with methods introduced since 1991
including the use of high-pressure oxygen, herbal medicines,
surgery, nutrition, and physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
The therapy has provided various levels of success for 89
patients, or 80 percent of related cases, with 22 experiencing
full recovery and four returning to work.
</P>
<P>
While the majority of comatose patients treated have remained
in a vegetative state for an average 40 days, some have regained
consciousness within only one week.
</P>
<P>
The hospital's therapeutic methods, all of which are listed in
the work entitled "Comprehensive Treatment and Rehab Research on
Patients in Continuous Vegetative State," have passed provincial
appraisals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
