<HEADLINE> Shanghai Closes Last Straw Pulp Production Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
metropolitan area, closed its last straw pulp production line on
August 1 to improve the water quality of the Huangpu River, the
major river bisecting the city.
</P>
<P>
The production of straw pulp, formerly one of the major raw
materials produced by Shanghai's paper mills, created heavy
effluent wastewater discharges into the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
Heavy wastewater pollution sparked the closure of numerous
paper mills in the upper reaches of the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua Paper Mill failed to thoroughly solve related
problems despite investing more than 18 million yuan (2.2 million
US dollars) in wastewater treatment efforts.
</P>
<P>
The mill conducted two years of intensive research and decided
to close its straw pulp production line in order to promote
environmental protection, a decision which will most likely reduce
the mill's profits by a substantial margin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
