<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 06:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Katyusha Rockets Fall in Israel's North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- In escalation of violent
clashes, several Katyusha rockets fell early this morning inside
Israel's north, injuring three people and damaging a Jewish
synagogue.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that some Katyusha rockets fell in
Israel's northern border town of Kiryat Shimona, no one was
injured in the shelling. But one rocket hit a populated area at
the so-called "pan-handle" of the Lake Kinneret (Or Sea of
Garlilee), damaging a synagogue and hurting one woman who was
injured by flying glass from shattered windows.
</P>
<P>
Local residents heard loud explosions at about 6 a.m. in the
morning. The shelling could have caused more casualties if it
came a bit late because many people usually go to the synagogue
to do the morning prayer.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the attack, but Israel
suspected it to be carried out by the anti-Israeli Hezbollah
(Party of God) guerrilla forces which have been fighting
Israel's occupation of South Lebanon. But in the past, the
militant Palestinian groups based in south Lebanon also shelled
occasionally Israel's north in a bid to escalate the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Today's Katyusha shelling is a sign of escalated clashes
between Israel and the Hezbollah forces which have vowed to
retaliate for the Monday killing of five Hezbollah fighters,
including two commanders, in north of the Israeli-claimed South
Lebanon Security Zone. The five were killed in the explosion of
a roadside bomb planned by Israeli special army units.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Hezbollah forces heavily shelled Israeli army
positions along the northern border Wednesday night with rocket
and mortar bombardments. A number of rounds fell inside Israeli
territory, but there were no casualties.
</P>
<P>
One Lebanese mother and her two children were killed in the
security zone in the explosion of a roadside bomb suspected by
Israel to be planted by Hezbollah. Meanwhile, a soldier from the
pro-Israeli South Lebanese Army was killed when his car hit a
roadside bomb.
</P>
<P>
This morning's shelling was launched after Israeli defense
officials tried to calm the situation by sending out a message
that Israel did not intend to escalate the tension.
</P>
<P>
Both Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Northern Command
commander Amiram Levine, who visited Kiryat Shimona Thursday,
said Israel would try to avoid an escalation by ordering its
troops to exercise restraint following the Wednesday shelling.
</P>
<P>
But they warned Hezbollah against making a mistake by
carrying on the rocket attack in violation of the ceasefire
understanding reached in April last year after Israel's Operation
Grapes of Wrath. In the ceasefire accord, both sides have
promised to refrain from targeting civilians and using the civilian
cover for any military attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India to Meet on 1950 Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and India will hold
foreign secretary level talks on August 19 in New Delhi to review
the 1950 Treaty of Peace and Friendship, Nepali Foreign Minister
Kamal Thapa said.
</P>
<P>
Thapa made the remark Thursday when answering questions at the
Lower House, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
While visiting Nepal in early June, Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral and his Nepali counterpart Lokendra Bahadur Chand
both agreed that at the next meeting of the foreign secretaries to
be held in two months, all issues of bilateral interest including
those related to the 1950 Treaty would be discussed.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed by a newly independent India and the
about-to-collapse Rana regime in Kathmandu, has come under sharp
criticism from all sides in Nepal in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Critics say some of the treaty's clauses infringe upon Nepal's
sovereignty and fail to reflect the present-day realities as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
