<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Job Seekers Turn To New Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan job seekers are
turning to new labor markets instead of the traditional Middle
East, according to bank sector sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the number of Sri Lanka migrant workers to the
Middle East are declining while the number of migrants to the
Maldives, Singapore, Hongkong and Italy are increasing.
</P>
<P>
But still the bulk of Sri Lanka's migrant workers of about half
a million is in the Middle East. The majority of Sri Lankans who
go to the new destinations are low paid housemaids and unskilled
workers.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore 81 percent of Sri Lankan migrant workers are
housemaids while in the case of the Maldives development of the
tourist industry there has contributed to the increased demand for
foreign labor, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
The structure of the demand for labor is biased towards
unskilled labor. About 91 percent of the female migrants are
employed as housemaids while 44 percent of the male migrants are
unskilled laborers.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan workers have been employed increasingly in
Singapore, Hong Kong and Italy recent years, said the sources,
adding that Sri Lanka seeks to extend its labor market there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
