<HEADLINE> More Disabled People In Shanghai Going to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 8 (Xinhua) -- When his long-time dream of
going to college finally came true two years ago, Yuan Jifeng, who
has a disability, decided to be number one in his class.
</P>
<P>
Yuan is a student at China's first college for people with
disabilities, which was started by Shanghai Television University
and Shanghai Disabled Persons' Federation in 1995. Its courses
include accounting, foreign languages, computers, and secretarial
training.
</P>
<P>
For convenience sake, the college has established branches all
over Shanghai, so that, in addition to television classes,
teachers provide one-on-one instruction. Tuition for disabled
students has been reduced, and they are provided with free video
tapes of the class.
</P>
<P>
One branch in the Huangpu District has opened four computer
classes for the hearing- and speech-impaired, where a professional
lectures from the podium, while another teacher translates using
sign language.
</P>
<P>
So far the college has 159 students, one of whom, Yuan Jifeng,
who has received high grades for two years, says, "I have never
missed a class even if it rains or snows." 
</P>
</TEXT>
