<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Making Headway in NW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region has been leading the country in promoting the private
sector by maintaining annual increases of more than 30 percent in
employees, registered capital, output, and sales.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the region had more than 80,000
privately-run businesses, which have become an important
contributor to local revenues.
</P>
<P>
Ye Tingzhu, who owns a private business in Zhongning County,
made money through trade and transportation. Then he spent 1.6
million yuan on a 2.4-km water diversion project to cultivate
nearly 100 ha of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Another example is Luo Fugui in Zhongwei County, who spent
three million yuan on a cattle farm that raises 1,000 head
annually.
</P>
<P>
This private sector has begun to shift from small-scale street
sales to large-scale technology-intensive operations. As a result,
there are 378 private businesses with over a million yuan in
registered capital, 51 of them have more than five million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Of those private businesses, 315 focus on science and
technology and have more than 200 million yuan in output value
annually, and 16 million yuan in profits.
</P>
<P>
The sector in fact adds 20,000 jobs every year and pays 600
million yuan in wages.
</P>
<P>
The region now has 299 farm produce markets, 80 percent of
whose managers are private business people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asia Sees Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- After a month-long turmoil,
Southeast Asian currency markets are becoming relatively quiet, as
countries in the region have taken a series of measures to deal
with speculations and maintain their economic growth.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, a property-related economic crisis and currency
speculations forced Thailand to allow its currency to slide
against the U.S. dollar, unleashing the world's worst financial
storm since the Mexico crisis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The crisis spilled over to the rest of Southeast Asia, and the
Philippines was forced to float its peso, while Indonesia had to
widen the trading band for the rupiah. Most currencies in the
region, including the Malaysian ringgit and Singapore dollar, have
devalued to their lowest in years during the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Now the currency markets have calmed down although some
currencies remain under pressure. On Thursday, the Philippine
currency, which devalued to 30 pesos to the U.S. dollar four weeks
ago, appreciated to 28.494 pesos against the greenback from 28.514
pesos in the previous day, while other currencies also gained
ground.
</P>
<P>
Why did the economic clouds pass the region violently but
quickly? Analysts hold that there are three main factors behind
the gradual stabilization of the currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
First of all, a series of new anti-speculation regulations
adopted by the countries concerned have forced speculators to make
a retreat.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, the Malaysian Central Bank ordered domestic banks
not to lend more than 2 million U.S. dollars in ringgit through
the swaps market to any offshore counterpart.
</P>
<P>
By introducing capital control, economists said, the bank
intends to cut off the supply of ringgit for offshore investors to
sell short.
</P>
<P>
Short-selling involves the sale of borrowed currency with the
intent of buying it back at lower prices; it can be used to hedge
against movements in the currency markets or for speculative
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Since May this year, short-sellers have been instrumental in
forcing depreciation of most Southeast Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the central bank tightened rules two weeks
ago on foreign exchange trading to reduce speculative demand for
dollars.
</P>
<P>
All non-deliverable forward contracts of onshore banks to sell
dollars to non-residents must get the approval of the central
bank. The rules will remain in effect for three months.
</P>
<P>
The second main factor is that the countries concerned seek
loans from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and other
official lenders to increase their foreign exchange reserves and
strengthen confidence of investors in the regional economies.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government's decision to accept an International
Monetary Fund (IMF) bailout of the country's flagging economy has
promoted currency stabilization in the region.
</P>
<P>
Announcing an economic recovery plan Tuesday, the Thai
government said that it would seek 12 billion to 15 billion U.S.
dollars from the IMF and other official lenders as part of an IMF
standby arrangement.
</P>
<P>
On July 18, the IMF already approved a 1.1 billion dollar
package to shore up Philippine foreign currency reserves, which
were reduced to 9.6 billion dollars after the central bank spent
1.9 billion dollars to defend the peso against speculators.
</P>
<P>
The third main factor behind the gradual stabilization of
currencies in the region is the virtual abandonment of fixed
exchange rate system by Thailand, the Philippines and other
Southeast Asian countries during the turmoil period.
</P>
<P>
Since Southeast Asian nations have allowed their currencies to
float, speculators are risking potential losses in their
activities if they act unwisely, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0257 </DOCNO>
