<HEADLINE> Romania Shuts Down Loss-Making Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Romanian Prime Minister Victor
Ciorbea said today that he was shutting down 14 large-scale
loss-making factories in a major step to readjust the nation's
industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing on Romania's economic reform programs,
Ciorbea said 21,000 workers will lose their jobs as a result of
the shutdown.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he will also soon close three of the
nine oil refineries in the country due to their poor performance.
</P>
<P>
The current oil processing capacity in Romania is over 30
million tons a year. However, only half of the refineries'
productive potential has been tapped.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea said previous economic reforms have succeeded in
bringing the nation's inflation rate from 20.8 percent during the
January to March period down to only 1 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade deficit in the first six months of this year
dropped to half of that in the same period last year. The total
trade deficit in 1996 was 1.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said his government also plans to provide equal preferential
policies to investors both at home and from abroad, in a bid to
encourage domestic investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
