<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Leading In Privatizing Small State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A brewery in Yibin County, in
southwest China's Sichuan Province, used to be a wholly
state-owned enterprise, but not any more.
</P>
<P>
The state now only owns 350,000 yuan of its property, which is
valued at 3.28 million yuan, the larger part having been sold to
employes.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan has taken the lead in the country's efforts to save the
large number of poorly-managed small state-owned enterprises through
public sales. More than 3,700 state-owned companies have changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
"I'm surprised at the enthusiasm shown by others in purchasing
state properties," an employee at the brewery said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the property rights system of China's state companies
has been a sensative issue, explains Prof. Liu Maocai, director of
the provincial Academy of Social Sciences, who noted that at
present most local small state firms' new owners are from the
private sector. "This is without doubt, a profound socio-economic
revolution," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In the process, many of these firms have gone from money-losers
to money-makers, something that has, interestingly, added value to
state assets, increased local revenues and the number of
employees, according to the Prof.Liu.
</P>
<P>
Governor Song Baorui recently told Xinhua that all of the
nearly 5,000 small state enterprises in Sichuan will mosty likely
adopt the system, although it is without precedent in China.
</P>
<P>
However, he explained, the change in ownership of these firms
can't shake up the state-owned sector, which is the country's
economic base. "We have yet to think about introducing reforms of
a similar kind to large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
