<HEADLINE> Argentine's Infant Mortality Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Argentine's infant mortality
rate dropped from 25.6 per thousand in 1990 to 22.2 per thousand
in 1995, Health Minister Alberto Mazza said today.
</P>
<P>
Lastest statistics show that preliminary figures for 1996 had
also fallen, he said.
</P>
<P>
The mother-children project, which had helped improve the
health situation for mothers and children during recent years, had
contributed to the fall in the mortality rate, Mazza said.
</P>
<P>
The 160-million-U.S.-dollar project, intended to provide food,
milk and care for mothers and children, has entered its second
stage financed by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
During the new stage, about 500 health centers for mothers and
children will be established and seven hospitals be refurbished,
the minister said. 
