<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina-Chile Gas Pipeline Inaugurated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem and his Chilean counterpart, Eduardo Frei, today inaugurated
the Gasandes Gasoduct, a gas pipeline connecting the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The works constitute "a visible and material proof of the
brotherhood of the two peoples," Menem said at the inauguration
ceremony held at the Argentine end of the pipeline, on Gloria
mountain, in the province of Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
"The Andean mountain chain is not a barrier, but an open
passage between neighbors who love and respect each other," Menem
said.
</P>
<P>
The 465-kilometer Gasandes pipeline, a bilateral project with
an investment of 350 million U.S. dollar, starts from the La Mora
Station, south Mendoza, and ends in Santiago, the Chilean capital.
</P>
<P>
At present, the gasoduct carries three million cubic meters of
natural gas a day from Argentina to Chile, to supply a
thermoelectric plant and a housing network in the Chilean capital.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the volume of natural gas carried by the
gasoduct to Chile each day will reach 5.5 million cubic meters by
next March, 10 million by the year 2000, and 20 million by 2017.
</P>
<P>
The gasoduct, which was built under a 1994 gas protocol, is the
second gasoduct built between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The first pipeline, which was inaugurated in January this year,
carries gas from Argentina's Tierra del Fuego to Punta Arenas in
Chile. It has a capacity of 1.5 million cubic meters each day.
</P>
<P>
After the inauguration ceremony in Argentine, the two
presidents left for Chile to preside in the afternoon over the
inauguration of the same works in Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Reach Agreement on Match-fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The jury finally announced
Thursday on Winchester Crown Court, England, that footballers Hans
Segers and John Fashanu, and Malaysian businessman Heng Suan Lim
were not guilty of alleging match-fixing in the English
Premiership.
</P>
<P>
Lim, Fashanu and former Liverpool goalkeeper Bruce Grobbelaar
were also found innocent on a second count after the 10-week
retrial.
</P>
<P>
But the jury foreman said Grobbelaar alone had not been cleared
on a final separate count.
</P>
<P>
It is still possible that Grobbelaar will be charged of
corruption because he was paid 2,000 pounds (about 3,000
U.S. dollars) from his former business partner Chris Vincent to
deliberately let the goal in.
</P>
<P>
The four men were charged of corruption earlier this year, but
no charge was verdicted in the first trial.
</P>
<P>
A year-long investigation was carried out by British police on
an alleged betting syndicate based in East Asia. The prosecution
claimed Lim was its representative in Britain.
</P>
<P>
During the trials, Lim admitted paying Grobbelaar and Segers
for help in forecasting the results of games, but all three
strenuously denied there was ever any plot to fix matches. None of
them admitted giving and accepting corrupt payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
