<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orbiting U.S. Space Shuttle Releases Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Discovery
today released a satellite for a health check on earth's ozone
layer hours after it soared into orbit.
</P>
<P>
The satellite was hauled overboard by the shuttle's robot arm
as the spaceship, with a total of 24 payloads, sailed 175 miles
(280 kilometers) above the earth, just south of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the satellite took place at 6:27 p.m. EST,
delayed about half an hour because of minor communications
difficulties between the spaceship and the the control room at the
Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
The satellite is supposed to spend nine days flying free of
Discovery, measuring atmospheric gases and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
During that time, NASA and the German space agency will launch
66 small rockets and weather balloons as well as a research plane
to examine the same piece of sky at the same moment as the
satellite.
</P>
<P>
Findings of the satellite will help scientists better
understand ozone depletion and develop more precise meteorological
models.
</P>
<P>
Among the six astronauts aboard is Iceland's first astronaut,
Bjarni Tryggvason, who was born in Iceland and is now a Canadian
citizen.
</P>
<P>
The crew will retrieve the satellite before returning home on
August 18.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle blasted off into a hazy sky at 10:41 a.m. EST from
the Kennedy Space Center at Cape Canaveral, Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
