<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The private economy in southwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region has emerged as a dynamic force in
the development of agricultural and pastoral areas, with related
activities yielding 1996 revenues of 59 million yuan, or 7.1
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The region is now home to 38,000 private businesses, a dramatic
rise on the mere 489 enterprises in 1980. These businesses
employee 57,000 people, up 10-fold increase on 1980, and have
average capital of nearly 10,000 yuan (1,200 US dollars), up
substantially from 1,000 yuan (120 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The private sector's retail sales accounted for 42 percent of
total retail sales for the region, with private businesses
occupying the major part of the market.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises are involved in more industrial sectors and
hand in better economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises in the transportation sector are enjoying
the most rapid development, with success spilling over into the
trade and hospitality sectors, as well as various other
industries.
</P>
<P>
The transportation sector's goal of "building more roads and
gaining prosperity" has had a profound influence on rural workers
who account for near 20 percent of the total number of employees
in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The education level of self-employed people has jumped by five
percent annually since the 1980s, with people attaining either a
middle and high school education lelel accounting for more than 60
percent of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
