<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Do Business With New Cambodian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it will do business with the newly-elected first prime
minister of Cambodia and the process of the elections was not
"democratic."
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's National Assembly members voted Wednesday to accept
Foreign Minister Ung Huot's nomination as first prime minister to
replace Prince Norodom Ranariddh who was ousted by Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen on July 6.
</P>
<P>
"We'll be meeting with him in order to do business with the
government of Cambodia.... But we do not believe that he was
chosen democratically," State Department spokesman James Rubin
said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Rubin noted that Hun Sen had told U.S. envoy Stephen Solarz and
a delegation from the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) that Ranariddh's royalist party FUNCINPEC could present a
new prime minister candidate if it chooses to do so.
</P>
<P>
The United States has suspended aid to Cambodia for 30 days of
review because of the crisis in that Southeast Asian country. With
the period reaching its expiration, Rubin said the United States
"will not provide funds to go through the government of Cambodia,"
but humanitarian aid would continue to go to Cambodia through
non-governmental groups "to help the people of Cambodia." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0299 </DOCNO>
