<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Reports Strong Growth in 1st Half-Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Coal imports by Germany increased by
a robust 25 percent in the first half of 1997 from the same period
of 1995, the Association of German Coal Importers announced today.
</P>
<P>
The increase, mainly due to the expanded demand from power
plants, boosted German coal imports in the first six months to 11
million tons, amounting to 29 percent of the total coal
consumption in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The association meanwhile expected a much less growth in coal
imports for the second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Coal currently covers about 14 percent of the total energy
supply in Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM Rejects Karadzic's Offer to Face Trial at Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today rejected an offer by former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan
Karadzic to stand trial in a Serb court under the supervision of
the international war crime tribunal at Den Haag, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel stressed that the international tribunal at Den Haag had
indicted Karadzic as a war criminal and therefore had priority
over any national court.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no jurisdiction a la carte as imagined by
Karadzic," Kinkel added.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic, who has so far refused to face trial at Den Haag,
indicated in an interview with the German newspaper Sueddeutsche
Zeitung Wednesday that he would be willing to answer questions
concerning the war crime charges at a Serb court under the
supervision of the international tribunal and the international
community.
</P>
<P>
"This would be the only respectable way out of the present
dilemma," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Diplomat Commits Suicide in Ottawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Ukrainian diplomat committed
suicide here Wednesday by jumping from his apartment, said reports
today.
</P>
<P>
Borys Polyachenko, 44, jumped from a 19th floor window
Wednesday afternoon and landed on a balcony 17 floors below.
</P>
<P>
Police are treating the diplomat's death as a suicide, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian diplomat was due to return to his country this
weekend with his family as his posting at the embassy was ending,
police said.
</P>
<P>
He had been at the embassy for three and a half years as first
secretary in charge of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Police said the downtown building is Polyachenko's residence
and his family was home at the time but didn't witness the
incident.
</P>
<P>
"It was an unfortunate incident.... We deeply regret it," said
Andriy Marchenko, spokesman of the Ukrainian embassy, here today.
</P>
</TEXT>
