<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street turned
sharply lower this afternoon as the bond market began to slide
again, lifting interest rates further from last week's 17-month
low.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average dropped 71.31 points to
8,188.00, after it flirted the 8,300 mark in earlier trading.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 576.03 million
shares as against 565.22 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 9.13 to 951.19, and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.38 to 492.62.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 6.28 to 1,624.16. It failed to
extend its streak of six consecutive closing highs. The American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.99 to 652.07.
</P>
<P>
All four measures had closed at record highs Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As bonds turned lower in the afternoon following a
less-than-enthusiastic auction of new 30-year Treasury securities,
the yield on the long bond jumped to 6.53 percent, up from late
Wednesday's 6.49 percent.
</P>
<P>
The yield fell to a 17-month low of 6.29 percent last week as
bonds traders celebrated the federal budget deal. But rates shot
higher Friday after the release of some economic data that made a
tame inflation outlook less certain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
