<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Faults Netanyahu, Arafat on Accusation Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States today
criticized both Israeli and Palestinian leaders for trading
accusation that it said was not in the spirit of partnership for
the peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu earlier
today accused the Palestinian Authority of behaving "like a regime
facilitating terror, like Iran or Iraq or Libya,"
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said today, "It is hard
to fathom how one could compare Chairman (Yasser) Arafat to
Colonel (Muammar) Gaddafi. Chairman Arafat was on the White House
lawn with the president. He signed a peace agreement with the
Israelis. We regard him as a partner in our effort to find peace
in the Middle East."
</P>
<P>
He also criticized Palestinian leader Arafat for his remarks
which he said were "meaning battle with Israel."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Arafat's speech to the Palestine Liberation
Organization's Fatah faction when he said measures imposed by
Israel against the Palestinians following last week's suicide
bombing at a Jerusalem market amounted to a declaration of war,
and he was preparing "for battle" accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said, "To the extent that it (Arafat's remarks) is...
interpreted as meaning battle with Israel, we regard them as
counterproductive. And we think they should not be made."
</P>
<P>
U.S. mediator Dennis Ross is traveling to the Middle East
starting this weekend to make a new drive to revive the stalled
negotiations between the Israelis and Palestinians, suspended
since the Israeli government decided to build Jewish homes in Arab
East Jerusalem several months ago. And the situation is further
deteriorating in the region in the wake of Jerusalem's suicide
bombing last week that killed 15 people and injured more than 100.
</P>
<P>
Ross hopes to get agreement on resuming Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations on a timetable aiming for settlement ahead of the May
1999 goal set in the Oslo Accords, the basic document of the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will also travel to the
Middle East at the end of this month provided there is progress to
be made after Ross's mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
