<DOCNO> XIE19970808.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Allen Johnson Shines, Bagach Cursed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Allen Johnson of the United States
shocked the world with a year's world best in the men's 110-meter
hurdles, while Ukraine's men's shot put gold medallist Aleksandr
Bagach lost his world title after a positive doping test at the 6th
World Athletics Championships here today.
</P>
<P>
The United States boosted their lead on the medal table with five
golds, two silvers and five bronzes. American John Godina couldn't
stop laugh when he was given Bagach's stripped world title.
</P>
<P>
Germany added one more laurel after Astrid Kumbernuss triumphed in
the women's shot put, making her country place second with a 3-1-2
medal combination. Kenya still remains third overall with a 2-2-1.
</P>
<P>
The day also saw Robert Korzeniowski of Poland win the men's
50-kilometer walk, Annarita Sidoti of Italy bring her country the
first gold in the women's 10,000m walk, and Beatrice Faumuina of New
Zealand seize her first world title in the women's discus.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, defending champion and Olympic gold winner, bolted off the
blocks first to clock 12.93 seconds, the third best all time and only
0.02 seconds off the world record.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Colin Jackson of Britain, who had been tamed 18
months by poor form, hit his season's best to finish second in 13.05,
ahead of Igor Kovac of Slovak Republic.
</P>
<P>
"I just wanted to make sure I was out of the blocks ahead of
Jackson., so that he could not disturb my rhythym, " said Johnson
after the race.
</P>
<P>
Jackson wasn't disappointed. "I thought I might have enough for the
gold medal, but anyway this was the time and place for my top
performance. I am back to my best and Allen is at his best. A few more
weeks of training and we could have a great head-to-head battle to
crack the world record."
</P>
<P>
The athletics world was shocked by the scandal that three athletes
- Bagach, the men's 400m hurdler Pascal Maran of France and women's
triple jumper Oxana Zelinskaya of Kazakhstan - have been tested
positive for taking the stimulant ephedrine.
</P>
<P>
Following the recent decision by the IAAF Congress, these athletes
will be issued a public warning. The results they achieved at the
current championships have been cancelled.
</P>
<P>
Another world leading performance was produced by Sidoti, who led
all the way to win the women's 10,000m walk final in 42:55.49.
Olimpiada Ivanova of Russia and Olga Kardopoltseva of Belarus took the
silver and bronze.
</P>
<P>
"During the last three kilometers my legs were terribly aching.
This gold medal is for Rossella Giordano. She was supposed to compete
here but didn't feel in shape, and so I replaced her," said the small
Italian winner.
</P>
<P>
Kumbernuss, defending champion and Olympic gold medallist, took a
sweet revenge when she beat her nemesis Vita Pavlysh of Ukraine in the
women's shot put final by five centimeters. Her winning toss was 20.71
meters.
</P>
<P>
Pavlysh, who upset Kumbernuss at the World Indoor Championships
this year, tried hard to turn the table but finished in vain.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to show who is the boss in the ring. I knew it would be
difficult and I couldn't get into the competition relaxed," said the
beamed German.
</P>
<P>
A disappointed Pavlysh said:"Here the difference between me and the
first was five centimeters. In the last competition the gap was 10
centimeters. But I am sure that I will break these bloody centimeters
to my favour eventually!"
</P>
<P>
In the day's most grievious battle - the men's 50km walk final -
Olympic champion Korzeniowski proved his victory at the Atlanta Games
was no fluke. He braved the hot sun to win the world title in 3:44:46,
leaving Jesus Angel Garcia of Spain in grimace for the second place 13
seconds behind him. Mexico's Miguel Angel Rodriguez finished third in
3:48:30.
</P>
<P>
Faumuina beat defending champion Ellina Zvereva of Belarus to win
the women's discus with a 66.82m toss. Natalya Sadova of Russia came
third.
</P>
<P>
In today's qualifications, France's Olympic champion Marie-Jose
Perec withdrew from the women's 200m semifinals due to an injury. That
gave Jamaice's Merlene Ottey's a good chance to defend her title.
</P>
<P>
Ottey, 37, showed a red hot form in the semifinal, clocking the
second fastest time in 22.26 seconds with a slow down pace in her
final strides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
