<HEADLINE> Camerounians Urged to Preserve Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State in charge of
economy and finance Edouard Mfoumou has called on Camerounians to
make concerted efforts to preserve economic achievements attained
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Mfoumou made the appeal at a press conference Wednesday on the
1997/1998 state budget here in Yaounde.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, a fight against unemployment and
poverty in Cameroun will be given priority in the 1997/1998
budgetary year.
</P>
<P>
Mfoumou insisted that Camerounians should have confidence in
government's efforts to re-launch the economy which has witnessed
steady growth of 5.5 percent since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the 1997/1998 state budget of 1,256
billion CFA Francs (about 2.4 billion U.S. Dollars) is realistic,
especially as Cameroun has renewed its confidence with world
financial institutions by signing a letter of intent to the
International Monetary Fund last month, outlining the country's
economic, financial and social programs for the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
